<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Corner Kicks Important Goal-scoring Tool </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Corner kicks have become an increasingly
important goal-scoring in the World Cup finals, FIFA Co-ordinator of
Techinical Study Group Jurg Nepfer said here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The percentage of goals scored directly with or immediately after a
corner kick has risen to 39.5 percent among the so-called "standard
situations" in the group competition from 13.3 percent in the same
phase four years ago in the United States, the Swiss said.
</P>
<P>
The standard situations include corner kick, direct free-kick,
throw-in and penalty.
</P>
<P>
Seventeen goals were netted in this way in 48 group matches as
compared to only four in 36 game in the last edition.
</P>
<P>
The matches also saw more involvement of midfielders in attacks in
front as they had scored 37 percent of goals, a substantial rise from
about 25 percent four years ago.
</P>
<P>
Nepfer also pointed out that although most goals were still scored
from a distance between goal area and penalty spot as they were in the
United States, more goals were scored from inside the goal area.
</P>
<P>
About 26 percent of the goals were blasted from inside the goal
area, a rise from 16 percent in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Late goals also dominated the group matches here, with as much as
28.6 percent of goals netted from a span of 76th to 90th minute while
four years ago the figure was 16.1 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
