<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, HKSAR Win Titles at International Dragon Boat Races </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 28 (Xinhua) -- A team from South China city of
Dongguan and the team from hosts Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR) won the men's and women's international championships
at the 1988 Hong Kong Dragon Boat Festival International Races
which closed on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Shan Tian team from Dongguan won the men's international
championship with a time of two minutes 49.71 seconds, followed by
boats from the Toronto Chinese Business Association and the
Amateur Rowing Association of the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The local side Yellow Pages Paddle Club team outpaced other
teams in the women's international races, finishing first in
3:15.21.
</P>
<P>
Fireblades Dragon Boat Rowing Team from the Philippines and New
York Metro Athletic Dragons team followed for the second and third
places, clocking 3:15.80 and 3:19.55 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The international mixed championship title went to New York
Metro Athletic Dragons team, which clocked the fastest time among
the eight finalists, of 3:01.86. Finishing second and third were
Drago-Fireblades Mixed Boat Team from the Philippines and the Hong
Kong SAR's Yellow Pages Paddle Club Mixed Team A.
</P>
<P>
Local teams Challenge Club Dragon Boat team and Yellow Pages
Paddle Club team took the men's and women's open championship
titles, the categories set for the local participants.
</P>
<P>
The two-day event attracted a field of 15 overseas teams and 90
local sides.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has been the forerunner in dragon boat racing,
hosting the world's earliest international races in 1967. This
year's was the 23rd for the annually-held series.
</P>
<P>
The races were jointly organized by the Hong Kong Tourist
Association and the Provisional Regional Urban Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
