<HEADLINE> Friendship between Chinese, U.S. Security Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Clinton's tour of the Great Wall made a dozen Chinese
and American plain-clothed security people, both men and women,
very busy. So there was practically no sightseeing for them and,
if any, they had all the same to be on high alert.
</P>
<P>
When President Clinton and his party left the Wall section at
Mutianyu, the security people were relaxed and at ease. And at the
proposal of their Chinese counterparts, they were happy to pose for
pictures together against the backdrop of the Great Wall.
</P>
<P>
The security men of both countries worked in close cooperation
during the Clintons' stay in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
-- Sorry, Cops, I Took "Dinner Invitation Card" for "Great Wall
</P>
<P>
Coverage Permit"
</P>
<P>
This morning, seven to eight American reporters were kept out
of the entrance of the Great Wall section at Mutianyu, since they
did not bring along the pass permit with them. But they were eager
to cover the Clintons' tour, and they were at a loss what to do.
</P>
<P>
The reason was that they do not know a singled word of the
Chinese and mistakenly took tonight's green invitation card for
dinner for their green permit to tour the Great Wall, as the two
kinds of cards very much resembled each other.
</P>
<P>
Finally, these reporters were allowed to follow the president
only when they won the approval of the Chinese Foreign Ministry
and the U.S. embassy after consultations.
</P>
<P>
-- Surfing Clinton's China Visit on Internet
</P>
<P>
A news-aware Internet service provider of Shanghai opened a
bilingual Website for President Clinton's China Trip.
</P>
<P>
Surfers can sort out and download the related information in
both Chinese and English on the U.S. president's activities during
his China trip, especially in Shanghai, the third leg of his
nine-day visit to China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
