<HEADLINE> Annan Desires to Defuse Tension in South Asia: Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 28 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Special Envoy Alvaro de
Soto said here Sunday that Secretary General Kofi Annan was
concerned over the rising tension in South Asia after India and
Pakistan conducted nuclear tests in May.
</P>
<P>
"The secretary general is concerned about the turn of events
that occurred in the region and that is why he has taken unusual
steps by sending me here," Soto told reporters after meeting with
Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan.
</P>
<P>
Soto said Annan is keen to visit the region yet the dates have
not been finalized.
</P>
<P>
"I had very useful talks with Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub," he
said. "I shall be reporting to the secretary general promptly."
</P>
<P>
According to a press release by the Foreign Office, during the
talks, Gohar welcomed the U.N. envoy's visit as representing a
first step towards an effective and sustained engagement by the
U.N. on the issue of peace and security in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
Soto expressed the secretary general's desire to defuse
tensions in the region through resolution of the problems
bedeviling the relations between Pakistan and India, the release
said.
</P>
<P>
Soto, who came here from Bangladeshi capital Dhaka Sunday
morning, will also call on Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and deliver
a message from the U.N. secretary general.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone conversation with Sharif two weeks ago, Annan
expressed the desire to send his special envoy to Pakistan and
India in a move to help resolve disputes between the two
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
The envoy would make arrangements for his visit to the region,
Annan said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has welcomed the secretary general's move while India
refused to receive the envoy as it opposes any outside mediation
on the disputes between Pakistan and India.
</P>
<P>
Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina just concluded her
brief visits to India and Pakistan. Hasina also expressed
willingness to mediate between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
