<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac Bestows Honor on Tutu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Visiting French President
Jacques Chirac Sunday decorated archbishop Desmond Tutu, chairman
of South Africa's Truth and Reconciliation Commission (TRC), with
the Grand Officer of the Legion of Honor, France's highest award
for non-heads of state.
</P>
<P>
Chirac, who was on a three-day state visit here, bestowed the
honor on the tiny cleric at a breakfast attended by about 10
South African personalities in Cape Town, a report reaching here
said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Friday, Chirac also presented South African Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki with the honor.
</P>
<P>
He paid tribute to Tutu, a Nobel peace prize laureate, for his
role in fighting for reconciliation in a new democratic South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
He said Tutu was "a man who was and is the conscience and
inspiration of South Africa."
</P>
<P>
The TRC special tribunal was set up in 1995 to bring to light
the grave human rights violations committed on all sides in the
apartheid days, and to grant amnesty to those who repent.
</P>
<P>
Tutu said the award was encouragement for the new South
Africa. He thanked the French people for their support to South
Africa during the struggle for freedom.
</P>
<P>
Chirac was due to leave Cape Town on Sunday afternoon for the
Mozambican capital of Maputo on the third leg of his six-day tour
of southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
Chirac's four-nation tour started with a 24-hour stop in the
western desert nation of Namibia and will end with a trip to
Angola. 
</P>
</TEXT>
