<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Learn From Uganda's AIDS Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Minister of Gender in
the President's Office Oppah Rushesha-Muchinguri will next week
lead a delegation to Uganda to study how Kampala has managed to
lower the levels of HIV/AIDS infections among its people.
</P>
<P>
The delegation will include officials from the ministry of
health and child welfare, representatives from the National AIDS
Control Program (NACP), youths and other organizations involved
in the fight against the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
The minister told the Zimbabwe News Agency over the weekend
that the delegation was going to study Uganda's success story and
see how its programs could be applied to Zimbabwe's situation.
</P>
<P>
Uganda was ranked the country with the highest numbers of
HIV/AIDS infections in Africa in the early 1990's and it has
since embarked on programs to conscientize people on the scourge
and the numbers of recorded infections haved drastically dropped.
</P>
<P>
''This week-long trip should be able to help us because we
have a problem that needs political will if the country is to
survive,'' Rushesha-Muchinguri said, adding, ''so basically we
are going to study the Ugandan situation and how they managed to
turn their situation around.''
</P>
<P>
According to the current estimates, an estimated two million
Zimbabweans are infected with HIV in a country of about 12.5
million people. About 700 people said to be dying every week
from AIDS. 
</P>
</TEXT>
