<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schumacher Wins French Grand Prix Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Michael Schumacher led a 1-2 finish
of his Ferrari team to win the title of the French Grand Prix in
Magny Cours of France on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He closed within six points of Mika Hakkinen with half the
season to go. Hakkinen still leads the drivers standings with 50
points while Schumacher moved up to 44.
</P>
<P>
Schumacher's Ferrari teammate, Eddie Irvine, acting a a buffer
between Schumacher and Hakkinen for most of the race, came in
second, 19.5 seconds behind.
</P>
<P>
A frustrated Hakkinen in a McLaren-Mercedes was third, barely
behind Irvine after trying to pass him for the last 15 laps of the
race.
</P>
<P>
It was the first 1-2 finish for Ferrari since the Spanish Grand
Prix in 1990 when Alan Prost and Nigel Mansell took the top two
slots for the red cars.
</P>
<P>
Schumacher clocked one hour 34 minutes, 45.026 seconds for the
71 laps of the 4.25-kilometer Magny Cours circuit. He averaged
190.963 kph for the 301.75 kilometers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
