<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Rejects Netanyahu's Proposal for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
Sunday denounced Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's
proposal for holding an international conference as an attempt to
change the basis of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters in Gaza, Arafat condemned Netanyahu for
trying to evade Israeli commitments to the signed peace accords by
proposing another international conference on the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He urged Netanyahu to respect the principles laid down in the
1991 Madrid Middle East peace conference and implement the Oslo
accords.
</P>
<P>
Senior Palestinian negotiator Hasan Asfour accused Netanyahu of
trying to kill the peace process. "The only thing he (Netanyahu)
takes seriously is killing the peace process," he said.
</P>
<P>
In an interview published Saturday on a Spanish newspaper,
Netanyahu suggested Europe host a Madrid II conference to revive
the multilateral Israeli-Arab talks to tackle Mideast regional
issues, but not the Israeli-Palestinian peace deadlock
specifically.
</P>
<P>
The Madrid peace conference, convened in 1991 under the
auspices of the U.S. and the former Soviet Union, created the
framework for subsequent bilateral and multilateral talks between
Israel and its Arab neighbors. It also formulated the landmark
land-for-peace principle, the cornerstone of the current peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's proposal was swiftly rejected by Egypt and Syria,
which charged him for attempting to torpedo the peace process by
overturning all the exiting principles and agreements.
</P>
<P>
Even back home, Netanyahu's proposal came under fire from
both the coalition and opposition politicians.
</P>
<P>
Education Minister Yitzhak Levy, head of the far-right
coalition partner National Religious Party, said there is no need
to convene another conference and efforts should be concentrated
on the final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
The leading opposition Labor Party's lawmaker Yossi Beilin said
Netanyahu proposed the idea only to "manipulate the media and the
public" by distracting their attention from the implementation of
existing agreements.
</P>
<P>
He added that Netanyahu knew well that there was no chance of
success for his proposal, because no country would attend such
conference.
</P>
<P>
Another opposition lawmaker Yossi Sarid, leader of the Meretz
Party, also said that Netanyahu's proposal would not succeed
because "no country will go to Madrid or elsewhere while the
Israeli-Palestinian negotiations are deadlocked."
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Israel Radio Sunday, Netanyahu defended
his proposal, saying it was aimed at complementing the American
initiative and not replacing it.
</P>
<P>
He blamed the Palestinians for holding up progress in the peace
process by refusing to honor their commitments. But he predicted
that the long overdue second Israeli troop redeployment in the
West Bank would be completed by the end of July.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian peace process has been stalled since
early last year, and the present sticking point is Israel's delay
in carrying out the second redeployment. The U.S. is now pressing
Netanyahu to accept its proposal for a 13.1 percent pullback in
order to revive the peace talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
