<DOCNO> XIE19980629.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-28 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Caution U.S. Against Vetoing Arab </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinians Sunday cautioned
the United States against vetoing an Arab draft resolution at the
United Nations Security Council on denouncing an Israeli plan to
expand the authority of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
If the U.S. exercises the veto power, then it will be showing
its "overt tilt" towards Israel, Palestinian ambassador in Cairo
Zohdi al-Quddra told the Egyptian Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council is scheduled to debate on Tuesday the
draft resolution outlined by the Palestinian National Authority
and supported by the Arab League, which calls on Israel to refrain
from unilateral actions.
</P>
<P>
The PNA has the "right to resort to the Security Council to
halt the implementation of Israel's decision to expand the
boundaries of Jerusalem and alter its status," al-Quddra said.
</P>
<P>
Last Sunday, the Israeli cabinet approved a plan which will set
up an "umbrella authority" for Jerusalem over eight West Bank
Jewish settlements to the east, north and south of the city.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian diplomat criticized the United States for its
"puzzling" stand on the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Although the U.S. has denounced Israel's decision, it objects
to the PNA's lodging an official complaint with the Security
Council to address this grave violation, al-Quddra said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the U.S. to pressure Israel to rescind the "foolish
decisions," warning against an explosion of the situation in the
region.
</P>
<P>
"Nobody can imagine what the Palestinian and Arab reaction
would be if (Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin) Netanyahu carries
out his expansionist schemes in Jerusalem," he said.
</P>
<P>
Under agreements signed between the Palestinians and Israel,
neither side should take unilateral actions to change the status
of Jerusalem, whose issue will be negotiated in the final status
talks for a permanent agreement.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Arab League has started a drive to secure the
endorsement of the draft resolution.
</P>
<P>
Arab League Secretary General Ahmed Esmat Abdel-Meguid has
contacted the European Union and Russia on the issue. He will
discuss the issue with the chiefs of the U.N., the Organization of
African Unity and the Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC)
as well as King Hassan II of Morocco, who heads OIC's Jerusalem
Committee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
