<HEADLINE> Iranian President Calls for Anti-drug Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami
Sunday called for cooperation between Iran and Colombia in efforts
to combat drug trafficking, the Iranian news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with visiting Colombian Parliament Speaker Carlos
Ardila Ballesteros, Khatami said fighting narcotics is one of the
areas in which the two countries can exchange experience and
expand cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"Considering it as a human and Islamic duty, Iran spends
significant amount of energy and resources to prevent trafficking
of drugs to European countries," the official news agency quote
him as saying.
</P>
<P>
Khatami termed narcotics as one of the major threats to Iran,
saying his country has sacrificed many lives in combating the
menace.
</P>
<P>
Iran launched nationwide anti-drug campaigns in 1989 when it
adopted a strict anti-drug law.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the country seized some 195 tonnes of narcotics.
</P>
<P>
Khatami said that Tehran and Bogota can also cooperate within
the Non-Aligned Movement, noting that Iran seeks peace and
tranquillity for the mankind.
</P>
<P>
He called for respect for the rights, dignity and equality of
all nations.
</P>
<P>
At the turn of the century, "we should prove that the future
world is one with no masters and one which heralds equal rights
for all nations," he said
</P>
<P>
The Colombian parliament speaker stressed the importance of
expanding Bogota-Tehran ties.
</P>
<P>
"All developing countries should come together to prevent
formation of a unipolar world," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ballesteros arrived here Friday and has since held talks with
his Iranian counterpart Nateq Nouri, Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi and other senior officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
