<HEADLINE> UN Observer Mission Leader Replaces Beye to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Military leader of the U.N.
Observer Mission in Angola Kofi Obeng will replace Blondin Beye
as temporary chairman of the Joint Commission on Peace Process
to mediate peace in the country, the commission said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made after a light aircraft carrying U.N.
representative to Angola Beye crashed Friday evening near
Abidjan, Cote d'Ivoire on his tour of five western African
countries to enlist support for the peace process in Angola.
</P>
<P>
At a special session here, the commission urged the U.N. and
the international community to explain the reason why Beye's
plane had crashed.
</P>
<P>
Beye was a great architect for Angola's peace and when
mourning over him, the commission will redouble its efforts to
mediate in Angola to fulfill Beye's dream of achieving national
reconciliation in the country, it said.
</P>
<P>
Beye had been en route to Abidjan from Togo in his five-nation
tour to discuss the halting peace process in Angola, and he was
feared dead in the accident and rescue workers in Cote d'Ivoire
resumed their efforts to reach the wreckage Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Beye headed U.N.-led talks in Zambia to end Angola's 19-year
civil war in 1993 and helped to broker a peace treaty between
the government and the rebel movement UNITA which was signed in
November 1994.
</P>
<P>
He then helped to oversee the implementation of the treaty,
acting as mediator between Angolan President Jose Eduardo Dos
Santos and Jonas Savimbi, leader of the National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
The commission urged U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan to name
a new U.N. envoy to Angola to replace Beye as soon as possible to
reduce the influence of Beye's death on Angola's peace process.
</P>
<P>
"If the news is true, then it is a tragedy, but we are still
committed firmly to the peace process," a senior UNITA official
said here Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
