<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Demands Iraqi Explanation of Assassination of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Iran renewed its demand to Iraqi
government Sunday for clear explanation of the assassination of
two Iranian Shiite leaders in southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The demand was put forward to the Iraqi charge d'affaires Saleh
Samarmad by the Director General of the Persian Gulf Department of
the Foreign Ministry Ali Aghsar Hojji, the officials news agency
IRNA reported .
</P>
<P>
Since April, two Iranian Shiite Muslim leaders have been killed
by unidentified gunmen in southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Ayatollah Sheikh Morteza Boroujerdi was gunned down in the
Shiite holy city Najaf on April 22 while performing evening
prayers. In a similar attack on June 19, Ayatollah Sheikh Mirza
Ali Gharavi and three others were shot dead on their way to Najaf
from Karbala.
</P>
<P>
Hojji told the Iraqi diplomat that Iraqi government is
responsible for protecting the lives of Shiite leaders and other
Iranian nationals residing in Iraq, the IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
He urged Iraq to shoulder its responsibility to apprehend those
perpetrators and prevent the repetition of such incidents.
</P>
<P>
Samarmad expressed sorrow over the assassinations on behalf of
the Iraqi government, saying that a top level committee has been
formed in Iraq to investigate the cases. He promised to arrest and
punish those who were responsible for the attacks.
</P>
<P>
Following the killing of Gharavi, Iran swiftly lodged a protest
to the Iraqi government over the repeated violence against Shiite
leaders, warning a repetition of such incident in future will
damage the bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Iraq fought a bloody war between 1980 and 1988 that
was triggered by territorial and religious disputes. Iraq is a
Sunni Muslim-dominated country, while Iran is largely a Shiite
Muslim state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
