<HEADLINE> Police Force Beefed up for England-Argentina Match </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAINT-ETIENNE, France, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Police force is almost
doubled for the World Cup second-round game between England and
Argentina following the violences in Marseille and Lens, local
officials said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Jean-Yves Audouin, Prefect of the Loire region, said the police
force stationed in Saint-Etienne will be increased to 1,500 from 900
on Sunday as fans began to pour into the city.
</P>
<P>
Some England fans clashed with Tunisian supporters outside the
stadium in a group match in Marseille, resulting in arrests and
deportations.
</P>
<P>
Officials said the match at Geoffroy-Guichard Stadium will not be
screened live in the Jean-Jaures Square in the town center because of
its limited capacity.
</P>
<P>
The local authorities also slammed an alcohol ban after 11:00 PM on
Monday and Tuesday in the city and its eight neighbouring towns.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutor Brice Robin said quick and firm legal trial will be held
concerning serious penal infringement such as physical assault on
police and damage to public property. 
</P>
</TEXT>
