<HEADLINE> Iraq Slams Clinton's Report to Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 28 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi official spokesman
Sunday criticized a report submitted by U.S. President Bill
Clinton to the U.S. Congress on Saturday for attempting to prolong
U.N. sanctions and interfere with Iraq's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency quoted the spokesman of the Ministry of
Culture and Information as saying that Clinton reiterated
U.S. government's aggressive stance against Iraq and threatened to
use force against the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been accusing Washington for prolonging the
U.N. sanctions imposed on Iraq following its invasion of Kuwait in
1990.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman noted that Clinton has renewed his government's
insistence on keeping in place the no-fly zones in north and
south of Iraq, in collaboration with the British government.
</P>
<P>
This is an illegal action that does not have the authorization
of the Security Council, only representing a defiance of the
U.N. Charter and all international laws, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman criticized Clinton for trying to justify his
government's decision to maintain military presence in the Gulf
under the name of ensuring the mission of U.N. arms inspections in
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"It is now crystal clear that these troops have not been
ordered by the United Nations or other countries. They have been
sent to the region to threaten Iraq's security, establish an
international terrorist force against Gulf countries and impose
U.S. hegemony over the region's oil, as part of the overall
U.S. policy of pursuing hegemony over the world," the spokesman
concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
