<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Following are economic briefs from
Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- Saudi Arabia is the biggest tires consuming market in
the Middle East because of its extensive road network and the
increasing number of cars, the Arab daily Al Hayat reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia now has a road network with a total length of over
450,000 kilometers and there are currently 8.5 million
vehicles. Taha Hussein, sales manager of Al Nasr Tyres company,
an offshoot of the International Al Thamir Group in Riyadh,
estimated that Saudi tires import in the past year was some 8.5
billion rials (2.7 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Hussein said that Saudi Arabia currently imports tires from
over 20 foreign countries, including the United States, Canada,
Japan, South Korea, China, Indonesia, Malaysia and some European
countries.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The cost of living index in Jordan has risen by 5.3
percent during the first four months of this year compared to the
same period last year, the Jordanian Central Bank said.
</P>
<P>
The index of food prices, representing about 14 percent of the
overall cost of living index, has increased by 5.4 points to 132.7
points from 127.3 points last year.
</P>
<P>
The index of housing prices and household expenses,
representing about 26.8 percent of the overall index, have risen
by about 3.5 points to 121.1 points from 117.6 points.
</P>
<P>
The index of commodities and other services, such as transport,
medical care and education, has also gone up by some 9 points.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal Ganzouri has promised to
eliminated all obstacles for foreign companies to invest in giant
projects in southern Egypt's Sinai and east Owainat, the Alam Al
Yom reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening session of the eighth environment
conference, Ganzouri pointed out that the government had decided to work
out a plan to simplify related legislations and procedures to
encourage foreign investment in all fields.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Jordanian Department of Standardization and
Specification and the Algerian Institute for Standardization
signed here Sunday an agreement to exchange experts and trainees
specialized in standardization technologies.
</P>
<P>
Under this agreement, the two countries will work together for
mutual recognition of the standardization certificates issued by
one another in various fields. The agreement also called for
unifying the standardization of the goods to be traded between
the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
