<DOCNO> XIE19980629.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola Shocked at Beye's Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Angolan Foreign Minister Venancio
de Moura said Sunday that he was shocked by the plane crash which
killed Blondin Beye, the United Nations special envoy to Angola.
</P>
<P>
However, he told the press during a mediating mission in
Guinea Bissau that although Beye's death will affect greatly the
Angolan peace process, the prospect for Angola is bright.
</P>
<P>
"If the news is true, then it is a tragedy, but we are still
committed firmly to the peace process," said a senior official
from the opposition National Union for the Total Independence of
Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
Portugal, one of the observer nations of the Angolan peace
process, also made a rapid response to the accident. Its
President Jorge Sampaio expressed his deep condolences to the
death of Beye, saying he had devoted his last moments to the
national reconciliation cause of the Angolan people.
</P>
<P>
South African Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo Sunday paid tribute
to Beye, saying in a statement that Beye had a passionate desire
to promote the best interest of all Angolans.
</P>
<P>
"If it is so, may his untimely death further galvanize the
forces of peace at this critical stage of the peace process in
Angola," Nzo said.
</P>
<P>
Beye left Angola on Friday for a visit to five African
countries, namely Sao Tome &AMP; Principe, Togo, Cote d'Ivoire, Gabon
and Burkina Faso, to seek support for Angola peace process from
their leaders.
</P>
<P>
On his way from Lome to Abidjan, his plane crashed on Friday
evening several kilometers away from the Ivorian commercial
capital.
</P>
<P>
Also on the plane were his spokesman, two political advisers,
a Portuguese officer, one of his Nigerian guard and two South
African pilots. The plane was rented by the United Nations from
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The Angola News Agency Sunday quoted a report from Abidjan as
saying that rescue people went deep into the wreckage spot after
finding it Saturday in a swamp near Abidjan and discovered
several bodies near the wreckage, which were hardly recognizable.
They also spotted Beye's passport and the passports of several
others.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, no survivor is found. A rescuer said 40 hours
after the plane crash that there is little possibility for
survivor as time draws on.
</P>
<P>
Residents near the crash venue said the Beechcraft 200 which
carried Beye crashed after it caught fire.
</P>
<P>
After the crash, the United States, Portugal, Russia and the
United Nations called on the Angolan government and UNITA to
honor Beye by carrying out the peace accord he spent the last
years of his life implementing.
</P>
<P>
"The best tribute the government and UNITA can pay to the
immense efforts and sacrifices of Maitre Beye and his colleagues,
is by rededicating themselves to lasting peace and genuine
reconciliation in Angola," they said in a statement issued in
Luanda and at U.N. headquarters.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Chief Kofi Anna, also said, "in this difficult time, I
once again appeal to all Angolans, in particular the government
of unity and national reconciliation and UNITA, to continue to
cooperate closely with the U.N. and to bring the peace process to
the earliest conclusion." 
</P>
</TEXT>
