<HEADLINE> Iranian Leader Defends Conservative Judiciary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 28 (Xinhua) -- In a move to defend the judiciary,
Iranian Supreme Leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei Sunday criticized
"certain persons, political groups and newspapers" for their
efforts to weaken it, Tehran radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to a group of judicial officials, Khamenei said that
any efforts aimed at weakening the judiciary is "irresponsible and
against the interest of the (Islamic) system."
</P>
<P>
Terming the judiciary as a pillar of the Islamic system, he
said that it provides Iran with security, justice, rule of law,
tranquility and social order.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian leader praised judiciary head Ayatollah Mohammad
Yazdi as "one of the most reliable and zealous clerics" in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei, meanwhile, called on the judiciary to remove its
"undeniable weak points" in enforcing justice so that the people
will feel rest and calm.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei's remark came after the judiciary came under fire of
the moderate groups and the media, which have called for Yazdi's
resignation.
</P>
<P>
The moderates have accused Yazdi and his conservative body of
trying to weaken the government of President Mohammad Khatami
after the judiciary insisted on putting the moderate Tehran Mayor
Gholamhussein Karbaschi on trial on graft charges.
</P>
<P>
Karbaschi's case was believed to be politically motivated by
the conservatives with an aim to avenge the disgraced defeat of
the conservatives in the presidential elections in May last year
because of Karbaschi's support for Khatami. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
