<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Urged to Prove Goodwill to Neighbors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The Gulf Cooperation Council
(GCC) Sunday urged Iraq to take necessary steps to prove goodwill
to its neighbors in an effort to achieve peace and stability in
the Gulf, Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued after a one-day meeting in Saudi capital
Riyadh, the foreign ministers of GCC's six members reiterated the
demand that Iraq "admit the mistakes of invading Kuwait and its
violation of Arab and international laws and norms."
</P>
<P>
The ministers reaffirmed support for the work of the U.N.
Special Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of eliminating Iraq's
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
They called on Iraq to cooperate with UNSCOM in a bid to help
lift the U.N. economic sanctions imposed on Iraq after its
invasion of Kuwait in 1990 and ease the plight of its people.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions can only be possibly lifted after UNSCOM
certifies that Iraq has scrapped the banned weapons.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers reiterated support for Iraq's
independence and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, a regional political and economic alliance, groups
Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and the United Arab
Emirates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
