<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-28 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait not Against Iraqi Presence at Arab Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti Foreign Minister
Sheikh Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah said Sunday Kuwait will not oppose
Iraq's attendance at a proposed Arab summit on the peace process
so to facilitate the summit's convening.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference in the Saudi capital Riyadh,
Al-Sabah pledged that Kuwait would not block any effort to hold an
Arab summit to discuss the Middle East peace process, the Kuwait
News Agency reported .
</P>
<P>
He noted that Kuwait has been attending the Arab League
meetings and "its seat is only a few steps away from the Iraqi
seat".
</P>
<P>
He said Kuwait and all other member states of the Gulf
Cooperation Council -- Bahrain, Qatar, Oman, Saudi Arabia and the
United Arab Emirates -- support the proposal for holding an Arab
summit.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to the proposal put forward by Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat for holding an Arab summit to confront the
Israeli intransigence that has stalled the peace process for over
15 months.
</P>
<P>
Most Arab countries have agreed to attend such summit, but no
agreement has been achieved due to the differences among some Arab
countries over what stance should take toward Israel.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sabah said the failure of the effort to convene an emergency
summit could lead to the deterioration of the situation in the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
But he suggested that the summit should be first coordinated
among Arab states bordering Israel, since they are the parties
involved in the peace process. Egypt, Jordan, Lebanon and Syria
are the countries that bordering Israel.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sabah's statements clarified earlier reports that Kuwait
might oppose holding an Arab summit if Iraq, which invaded Kuwait
in 1990, is invited. Many Arab countries believe that Iraq should
also be invited to the summit in order to demonstrate the Arab
unity in dealing with Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
