<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac Specifies France's Africa Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 28 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques
Chirac said France wants to cooperate with all African countries
and would allow Africans to solve their problems by themselves.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with South African national television, the
SABC, Chirac denied that France was trying to expand its "sphere
of influence" in Africa.
</P>
<P>
He said the word "sphere of influence" was right in the past.
"I would say, instead of sphere of influence, areas of
friendship."
</P>
<P>
In the interview broadcast Sunday night, Chirac said France's
Africa Policy is to extend its area of friendship with the rest
of Africa while maintaining its traditional relations with French
speaking countries.
</P>
<P>
"Traditionally we have very close relations with francophone
countries. We of course keep the same relations with francophone
countries.
</P>
<P>
"But we also want to extend our area of friendship. We want to
cooperate with the other countries of Africa, and specially with
southern Africa, and specially with the engine of Africa of
tomorrow, which is South Africa."
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that France and South Africa would not be rivals
on the continent. He said South Africa's influence would increase
in the rest of Africa and that was good.
</P>
<P>
"There will be no rivalry between France and South Africa. We
want to participate hand in hand with South Africa in partnership
to help countries in Africa."
</P>
<P>
He said South Africa would become a very powerful country in
the world, one of the main countries in the world. "The world is
to be a multi-polar world," he said.
</P>
<P>
Asked about France's stand on an international peace-keeping
force in Africa, Chirac said: "In general, we think that Africa's
problems should be solved by Africans."
</P>
<P>
"If Africans decide to have an international (peace-keeping)
force, and if they ask us to help... we would agree completely.
But that is their decision, not ours."
</P>
<P>
"In this regard, we didn't support the American proposition,"
said Chirac.
</P>
<P>
The United States failed to persuade African countries into
setting up a U.S.-led peace-keeping force in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Chirac said France also had different views with the Americans
on debt relief.
</P>
<P>
He said international and bilateral assistance is a necessity
to show solidarity with poor countries.
</P>
<P>
"That's why we fight for aid, not only for trade, and we win."
</P>
<P>
"We are in a world with globalization, which is a good thing,
because it allows rapid development. But this situation is also
dangerous, because poor countries may become poorer and poorer
and rich ones, richer and richer."
</P>
<P>
Asked about his position on an Organization of African Unity
(OAU) resolution on U.N. sanctions against Libya, Chirac said:
"France is not in favor of sanctions in general, today."
</P>
<P>
The OAU resolution demanded the suspension of U.N. sanctions
immediately. Should the suspension not be in place by July, OAU
members reserved the right to ignore the sanctions, according to
the resolution.
</P>
<P>
Chirac said it was always the poorest people that fell victims
of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
On bilateral relations with South Africa, Chirac said France
supported a free trade agreement between the European Union and
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
"I am sure the signature of the agreement between the European
Union and South Africa will be done before the end of the year."
</P>
<P>
He said France supported South Africa's bid for a permanent
seat on the United Nations Security Council. He also promised to
import more South African goods to seek a trade balance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
