<HEADLINE> Chinese Firm To Invest In Zambia Copper-mining Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The China Nonferrous Metal
Industry's Foreign Engineering and Construction (Group) Corp. has
signed an agreement with two Zambian companies on investment in a
copper-mining project in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
It is the first overseas mining project invested by the Chinese
nonferrous metal sector, according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the Chinese company will hold 85 percent
of the Chambishi Coppermine, while the rest goes to the two
Zambian partners.
</P>
<P>
The project, with an investment of 150 million U.S. dollars, is
designed to have an annual mining capacity of 1.83 million tons
and produce 110,000 tons of fine copper ore, which is equivalent
to 38,000 tons of copper.
</P>
<P>
The mine's known reserve is 44 million tons of copper ore, or
840,000 tons of copper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
