<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Floodwaters Rising in Yangtze River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The water level of the Yangtze River
near the capital of central China's Hubei Province reached 26.89
meters at 8 a.m. today, the highest June level in 100 years.
</P>
<P>
Due to torrential rains along the the upper and middle reaches
of the river, the water level in the Wuhan sector has been
constantly rising. Within the past 39 hours the water level
exceeded the warning level and is approaching the urgent level,
which is set at 27.30 meters, according to local sources.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Changsha, capital of central China's
Hunan Province, has been hit by its biggest flood since 1949.
</P>
<P>
Parts of the city's urban areas and a vast stretch of rural
areas, including 275 villages, have been flooded. Some 200,000
people were stranded by floodwaters. The losses are estimated at 4
billion yuan (481 million U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
