<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Pollution in China Serious, Top Legislator Says  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Water pollution in China is still
serious, with quality deteriorating and shortages worsening,
according to a top legislator.
</P>
<P>
Zou Jiahua, vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress, China's highest legislative body,
today made the remark at a meeting on enforcing the Law on the
Prevention and Control of Water Pollution.
</P>
<P>
"There may be a serious water crisis in China in the early
years of the coming century if no effective measures are taken in
law, economy and technology," Zou stressed.
</P>
<P>
Zou urged the governments and administrators at various levels
not to lower their guard on water pollution but to have a sense of
imminence and crisis.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to ensure the country has a safe and healthy water
environment and sustainable water supply, Zou said that government
officials should approach the issues of prevention and control of
water pollution, as well as the protection of water resources,
from the high plane of survival and development of the Chinese
nation.
</P>
<P>
According to a report by the Ministry of Water Resources, the
average per capita availability of water resources in China is
about 2400 tons annually, only a quarter of the world
average. China is considered one of the poorest countries in terms
of water resources.
</P>
<P>
With an ever-increasing population, the per capita availability
of water resources and water supply should continue going down,
the ministry report states.
</P>
<P>
Out of more than 600 large- and medium-size cities, nearly 400
are short of water and more than 110 are in desperate need of
water, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
In urban areas, it states, there is a need of water totaling 16
million tons daily. Some 30 billion tons are in short supply
annually for agriculture. This causes a loss of 230 billion yuan
in industrial production, and a grain deduction of 20 billion
kilograms every year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980629.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conference Ends on CPC's Rural Grassroots Units </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- A three-day national conference on
building the rural grassroots organizations of the Communist Party
of China (CPC) ended here today.
</P>
<P>
At the closing session, Vice-Premier Wen Jiabao, a member of
the CPC Central Committee Political Bureau, delivered a report on
the current situation of the country's agricultural sector and
what to do in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
Wen, who is also a member of the CPC Central Committee
Secretariat, urged the implementation of the Party's rural
policies to bring up farmers' initiatives, readjust and optimize
economic structures in the countryside, improve the rural
infrastructure, step up efforts to eradicate poverty, and build a
democratic system in villages.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Party's leadership over rural works should
be strengthened, while the roles of both the Party's grassroots
units and CPC members in the countryside should be brought into
full play. 
</P>
</TEXT>
