<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Parties Urges Int'l Support Over Border Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The nine leftist parties of
Nepal on Monday wrote to United Nations Secretary-General Kofi
Annan, appealing for international support against "encroachment
and intrusion" of Nepalese territory by India.
</P>
<P>
The letter, which is to be handed over to Annan via the U.N.
office here, said that India has been occupying about 19,600
hectares of land in Kalapani in far-western Nepal and has
stationed its armed personnel there since 1962.
</P>
<P>
Recently, India enlarged the occupied area and erected barriers
to prevent the movement of Nepalese citizens in their own
territory, the letter said.
</P>
<P>
"It constitutes a serious breach of international norms and a
provocation on the part of the Indian government," the letter
said. "We are, therefore, compelled to internationalize the issue
and mobilize the world opinion against this illegal occupation,
encroachment and intrusion of Nepalese territory by India."
</P>
<P>
It said there are encroachment and intrusions in other parts of
Nepal as well. The latest instance was in Pashupatinagar in
eastern Nepal where Indian armed personnel demolished the huts of
Nepalese citizens, erected barriers and planned to illegally
construct ranger posts there, it said.
</P>
<P>
"We are eager to settle the boundary issues with India within a
specific timeframe and on the basis of the Sugauli Treaty of 1816
and other documents and evidences," the letter said.
</P>
<P>
It noted that the nine leftist parties have launched a struggle
against the Indian occupation, encroachment and intrusion of
Nepalese territory.
</P>
<P>
The Joint Working Group between Nepal and India on boundary has
met twice but without any result, it said.
</P>
<P>
In recent months, the nine leftist parties including the
Communist Party of Nepal (Marxism-Leninism, CPN-ML), the third
largest in parliament, have raised their voice on the issue.
</P>
<P>
When Indian President K. R. Narayanan visited Nepal in late
May, they issued an open letter to him, demanding that the Indian
army withdraw immediately and that India stop encroaching upon the
Nepalese territory.
</P>
<P>
At the summer session of parliament which opened on Sunday, the
opposition parties demanded that the minority government under the
Nepali Congress party initiate necessary actions to press for the
immediate withdrawal of the Indian army from Kalapani and the
return of encroached land by India in the border areas.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Girija Prasad Koirala told the press early this
month that he would discuss with his Indian counterpart Atal
Bihari Vajpayee the issue of Kalapani on the sidelines of a summit
of the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation scheduled
for late July in Sri Lanka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
