<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Discloses Details of Nuclear Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan disclosed for the first
time on Monday that the six nuclear tests it conducted last month
included one main test, four sub-kiloton tests and one
miniaturized device, which were "totally contained and safe".
</P>
<P>
The main test was conducted on May 28 at 1516 local time in the
Raskoh range of Chagai, in the remote Balochistan province, said
an official press release received here Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"It was detonated by a telecommand station situated 10
kilometers from the zero point. The device was placed in a
one-kilometer tunnel with an over burden of 700-meter high
mountain," it said.
</P>
<P>
"The data gave a yield in accordance with our design
calculations," it said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the main test, "four sub-Kiloton tests were also
conducted in the same mountain range. Extensive technical data has
been generated from these experiments which are under examination
by our scientists," the release said.
</P>
<P>
The sixth test was conducted in the Kharan desert on May 30, at
1155 local time, it said.
</P>
<P>
"A miniaturized device was placed in an L-shaped underground
shaft that was 120-meter deep," it said. "The test gave a yield
which was about 60 percent of the first test and conformed to our
design value."
</P>
<P>
After these tests, an extensive survey was carried out for
detection of radiation at the test sites and their environment,
the release said.
</P>
<P>
"Surveys indicate that there has been no release of
radioactivity as a result of nuclear testing. The tests were
totally contained and safe," it added.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's nuclear tests followed five nuclear tests conducted
earlier by India. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
