<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Recruit Tanzanian Medical Staff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 29 (Xinhua) - Zimbabwe has requested
Tanzania to provide 380 nurses and doctors to meet the acute
shortage of the medics in its hospitals.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe wants to hire 300 nurses, 20 doctors, 13 psychiatrists
and medical staff, the local media reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian Ministry of Health has invited applications from
its medical staff who would like to work in Zimbabwe, but the
final agreement has not been signed by the two governments.
</P>
<P>
The salaries for the Tanzanian nurses and doctors will be paid
in U.S. Dollars ranging from 265 Dollars to a maximum of 570
Dollars per month.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean Minister for Health and Child-Welfare, Timothy
Stamps, has said that a large number of Zimbabwean medics have
left Zimbabwe to work in Botswana, South Africa, Britain and the
United States because they had been "offered better working
conditions and remuneration."
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's private hospitals also attract nurses and doctors
from government ones, reports said.  
