points to 2,621.1, around the midpoint of the day's trading range.
</P>
<P>
"There was strong buying in selected blue chips," Morgans
broker Simon Reed said.
</P>
<P>
Investors would be looking to low risk, "fairly safe" stocks in
the last couple of days before the end of Australia's financial
year of 1997-1998, he said.
</P>
<P>
Rupert Murdoch's media group News Corp led the charge and was
"shining after a strong performance on Wall Street over the
weekend," Reed said.
</P>
<P>
News Corp climbed 22 cents to 12.10 Australian dollars with the
preferred shares adding 16 cents to 10.50 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
It helped the all industrials index to add 38.4 points to
4,602.1 while a big slump in BHP shares dragged the all resources
index 13.6 points lower to 1,022.6 points.
</P>
<P>
Diversified mining giant BHP plunged 51 cents to 13.19
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The banking index rose 44.6 points to 5,724.0, with National
Australia Bank shares stacking on 29.9 cents to 21.35 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth Bank of Australia rose eight cents to 18.43
Australian dollars and ANZ bank climbed 10 cents to 11.23
Australian dollars but Westpac bank bucked the trend, slipping
four cents to 9.78 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the gold sector, the index dropped 15.4 points to 1,030.8
while the gold bullion spot price dipped 20 U.S. cents to 293.50
U.S. dollars per ounce in late Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 435.43 million shares worth 672.29
million U.S. dollars with falls outnumbering rises 641 to 585.
</P>
