<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Food Shortage Facing Southern Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Southern Africa will face a food
shortage because of reduced crop yields resulting from abnormal
rainfalls in different countries in the region in the 1997-1998
cropping season.
</P>
<P>
Reduced maize harvests compared to last year have been
forecast in all the countries in the region except in Malawi,
Mozambique, Angola and Swaziland, while Maize output declined by
nearly 70 percent in Lesotho because of poor rains, according to
a food security report of the Southern African Development
Community (SADC).
</P>
<P>
The latest food security assessment for the SADC region
indicates that regional maize supplies for the forthcoming
1998-1999 marketing year will be much less than the previous year
due to erratic rains in South Africa, Zimbabwe, Lesotho, Namibia
and part of Zambia, coupled with excessive rains and flooding in
Tanzania and Mozambique, Malawi and Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The maize production is expected to be 16.13 million tons in
the 1997-1998 harvesting season compared to last year's 17.05
million tons, said the report made available here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The region will have an overall maize deficit of up to 1.72
million tons compared to a shortfall of 204,000 tons for the
1997-1998 marketing year, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The regional production of all cereals combined amounts to
21.55 million tons against 22.38 million tons last year.
</P>
<P>
The production of the 1998 winter wheat crop is projected to
remain close to the 1997 harvest of 2.77 million tons while the
output of sorghum/millet has dropped to 1.92 million tons from
2.03 million tons last year.
</P>
<P>
An overall cereal deficit of 3.19 million tons have been
forecast for the 1998-1999 marketing year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980629.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S'pore Announces Measures to Stimulate Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 29 (Xinhua)-- Singapore Finance Minister
Richard Hu Tsu Tau on Monday announced a 68-point package of
off-budget measures to boost the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
Under the much-anticipated measures, an estimated 2 billion
Singapore dollars will be injected into the economy.
</P>
<P>
The package, covering all areas in the economy, includes
several tax concessions designed to help ease business costs
during the current economic downturn and help local business
obtain working capital in a situation of tight liquidity, the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
Based on revised revenue and expenditure estimate, the
introduction of the package will result in a budget deficit of
about 800 million Singapore dollars for fiscal 1998, he told
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The minister emphasized that these measures have 3 broad
objectives -- to reduce business costs, build economic
infrastructure and capabilities and help stabilize specific
sectors of the economy.
</P>
<P>
He also said that based on the worsening economic outlook in
the East Asia region, Singapore's Ministry of Trade and Industry
has revised down the country's GDP growth forecast to 0.5-1.5
percent for this year from 2.5 to 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
"We must brace ourselves for slower economic growth during the
next years of regional transition and recovery," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Some industries and companies will feel the fall in the
business demand and profits more acutely than others; Some have to
merge or relocate," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
