<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Okays Two Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Executive Committee of the
Bangladesh National Economic Council has approved two projects
worth 154.93 billion taka (about 3.15 billion U.S. dollars), media
reports here said Monday.
</P>
<P>
They are the Arsenic Mitigation Water Supply Project involving
1.79 billion taka (about 38.9 million dollars), and the Health and
Population Sector Program Implementation Plan worth 153.14 billion
taka (about 3.1 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The three-year Arsenic Mitigation Water Supply Project,
designed on an emergency basis to ensure supply of arsenic-free
water, will start next July, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
With a population of 127 million, Bangladesh is the most
seriously arsenic-polluted country in the world, where 52
districts out of a total 64, with a population of about 76.9
million, have been polluted.
</P>
<P>
The Health and Population Sector Program Implementation Plan
aims to check mother and child mortality rates and control
contagious diseases.
</P>
<P>
The five-year program, which is also scheduled to start next
July, also aims to reduce the fertility rate (3.2 percent at
present), increase peoples' life expectancy (now 59.5) and elevate
their nutritional status and health standards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
