<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets Hong Kong Youth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- President Jiang Zemin met this
morning with a Hong Kong youth delegation to discuss Chinese
history, culture and education at the Great Hall of the People.
</P>
<P>
The president plans to visit Hong Kong to join in celebrations
for the first anniversary of the homecoming of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
In talks with the 500-member delegation, the president said
that young people in Hong Kong represent the future of the region.
</P>
<P>
"Like young people in the inland areas of the motherland, you
are shouldering the same glorious duty and mission in the process
of the great Renaissance of the Chinese nation," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
He welcomed the Hong Kong delegates to visit the inland areas
and spoke highly of their activities of "knowing China's culture
and history, and caring about the future of the motherland".
</P>
<P>
Since the return of Hong Kong, the government of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (HKSAR), headed by Chief Executive
Tung Chee-hwa, has stablized the local economy, with the support
of the central government and under the principles of "one
country, two systems," "Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong," and
high autonomy, according to Jiang.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the goal for modernizing the motherland,
maintaining the long-term prosperity and stability of Hong Kong,
pushing the great cause of the reunification of the motherland is
to make the motherland strong and reinvigorate the nation.
</P>
<P>
Because of the 100 years of colonial rule, young people in Hong
Kong have insufficient knowledge about the history and culture of
the Chinese nation, and the history of the links between the Hong
Kong compatriots and the people in the inland areas, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
The president expressed his hope that, during their tour in the
inland areas, the young people from Hong Kong would learn more
about the history of the Chinese nation as well as the current
reform, opening-up and modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong delegation has visited local universities,
museums and historical sites. 
</P>
