<HEADLINE> UN Chief Expected to Visit Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 29 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Secretary-General
Kofi Annan is on the way for a visit to Nigeria to meet the
country's new leader General Abdulsalam Abubakar, according to
reports monitored here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Expected to be in the west African country Monday night, Annan,
and General Abubakar will discuss ways to solve Nigeria's current
political crisis and break its diplomatic isolation.
</P>
<P>
Annan's visit followed that by British Foreign Office Minister
Tony Lloyd who toured Nigeria last week on behalf of the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
His Commonwealth counterpart, Chief Emeka Anyaoku,
is in the country for discussions with the new head of
state, who assumed office after the sudden death of his
predecessor General Sani Abacha early this month.
</P>
<P>
The EU and the Commonwealth have imposed sanction packages on
Nigeria due to alleged violation of human rights and lack of
democracy.
</P>
<P>
The UN also consistently criticized the policies of the Abacha
administration, especially the violation of human rights.
</P>
<P>
In his inaugural statement, Abubakar promised to lead
Nigeria to national reconciliation and democracy. He has since
ordered the release of some 30 political detainees, including
former head of state Olusegun Obasanjo jailed for alleged
involvement in a coup plot.
</P>
<P>
The new leader also initiated nationwide consultations in
order to gather the ideas of various interest groups for solution
to the political transition of the military government.
</P>
<P>
All that the general has done so far has won wide welcome both
at home and abroad, particularly the West, which sees the actions
as good gesture for Nigeria to move toward democracy.
</P>
<P>
Both Lloyd and Anyaoku have expressed belief that Abubakar's
commitment to the democratization and release of political
detainees will pave the way for the resolution of Nigeria's
current political crisis and for its return to the international
community.
</P>
<P>
It is expected Annan's visit would help promote the Nigerian
military government's transition to civil rule program under the
leadership of General Abubakar.  
</P>
</TEXT>
