<HEADLINE> Weizman Calls for Early Elections, Netanyahu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Israeli President Ezer Weizman
on Monday called for early general elections in light of the
deadlocked peace process, but Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
rejected the idea.
</P>
<P>
Weizman made his call during a condolence visit to the family
of the fallen Israeli soldier Or Cohen in Jerusalem. Cohen, 19,
was killed in a roadside bomb blast by Lebanese guerrillas in
south Lebanon last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Israel has occupied a 1,200-square-kilometer border strip in
south Lebanon since 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its
northern areas from Lebanese guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
"The peace process has been dragged on so long and the best
thing to do is to organize the new general elections," Weizman
said.
</P>
<P>
Weizman pointed out that he has been waiting for a long time to
present his opinion for holding the general elections, saying it
could be the best way to break the impasse in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu and several other cabinet ministers reacted very
quickly to Weizman's call, blaming the president for taking a
political side with the left political parties.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters after his meeting here with Spanish Prime
Minister Jose Maria Aznar, Netanyahu said the new general
elections will only be held as scheduled, that is in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
He said he has been working around the clock to form a good
accord with the Palestinians, that could ensure the security for
the citizens of Israel.
</P>
<P>
He said nobody could shrink him from this commitment. He also
blamed the Palestinians for ignoring their commitments, saying
this is the reason why the peace process is deadlocked.
</P>
<P>
Other cabinet ministers, including Communications Minister
Limor Livnat and Agriculture and Environment Minister Rafael
Eitan, have slammed Weizman for making the call, and asked him to
be patient until progress is made in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
But the opposition parties such as the Labor and Meretz
welcomed Weizman's call, saying that they will initiate a
legislation bill to dissolve the Knesset (parliament). 
</P>
</TEXT>
