<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Steps up Protection of Intellectual Property Rights (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Chinese authorities recently
organized an ever-larger crackdown operation on copyright piracy,
crushing more than 2.8 million smuggled compact discs.
</P>
<P>
The destruction of illegal publications is not the only avenue
the Chinese government is taking to combat violations of
intellectual property rights (IPR). The revised Criminal Law of
the country includes punishment for IPR violators.
</P>
<P>
VCD vendors, who often stroll Beijing's Zhongguancun electronic
street for potential buyers, have become more wary. Some have
taken legitimate jobs rather than trading in pirate compact discs,
which could result in heavy fines or imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the illegal producers of such discs are facing
hard times because of stricter IPR laws and regulations.
</P>
<P>
Yin Pinghua, a 50-year-old man from eastern Jiangsu Province,
was sentenced to six years in prison and fined 300,000 yuan (about
36,000 U.S. dollars) last month. Yin was found guilty of pirating
more than 200,000 copies of best-selling Chinese dictionaries.
</P>
<P>
Beijing's judicial bodies have given Yin the harshest sentence
yet for copyright violations since the adoption of the revised
Criminal Law.
</P>
<P>
The new law added an intellectual property clause and a maximum
penalty of seven years in prison plus fines.
</P>
<P>
Chinese officials have been busy enforcing IPR violations.
Guangdong Province has destroyed more than six million pirated
VCD's in the past six months. Authorities have shut down and
dismantled 64 VCD production lines throughout China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
