<DOCNO> XIE19980629.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Calls on Europe to Hold More Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 29 (Xinhua) -- South African Finance
Minister Trevor Manuel has made a strong pitch to his French
counterpart, Dominique Strauss-Kahn, for the newly created
European Central Bank to hold 20 percent of its reserve in gold.
</P>
<P>
Meeting in Cape Town Sunday as French President Jacques Chirac
wound up his three-day visit to South Africa, Manuel and
Strauss-Kahn discussed a range of economic issues, Business Day
paper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Manuel repeated a call made by Deputy President Thabo Mbeki in
Davos, Switzerland, earlier this year for central banks to
reconsider plans to reduce their gold holdings.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, the world's biggest gold producer, has suffered
greatly since the international gold market tumbled last year as
a result of declining gold consumption by Asia during its
financial crisis, coupled by large sales of gold reserves by
central banks.
</P>
<P>
Strauss-Kahn had said the French Central Bank did not intend
reducing its holdings as a percentage of total reserves, but did
not say what they were.
</P>
<P>
The European Central Banks's president, Wim Duisenberg, said
recently the bank's six governors agreed that only 10 percent to
15 percent of its reserves would be held in gold. This translates
to about 900 tons of gold.
</P>
<P>
The figure is sharply down from the total gold reserves
currently held by the 11 European countries included in the first
wave of Monetary Union, which is to be launched next year.
</P>
<P>
The 11 countries collectively hold nearly 13,000 tons of gold
- equivalent to five years' supply from the world's mines.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Strauss-Kahn told Manuel that Japan's economic woes
could have a serious knock-on effect in Europe as European
commercial banks have great exposure in Japan, the Business Day
report said.
</P>
<P>
On the Euro, Strauss-Kahn predicted that growth rates in
Europe would rise to United States levels after the introduction
of the common currency. He expected the Euro to displace the
Dollar at least partly in its international role.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers had agreed that the United States should not
be allowed to dominate the Group 22, the grouping of G-8
industrialized nations with 14 more advanced developing
countries, including South Africa, the report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
