<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Steps up Protection of Intellectual Property Rights (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An official of the U.S. Consulate in Guangzhou witnessed the
large-scale destruction of discs on June 15.
</P>
<P>
"China showed its determination to protect IPR and combat
copyright piracy," he commented.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Customs officials also are taking steps to protect the
brand names of foreign businesses.
</P>
<P>
China adopted the Customs Regulation Concerning the Protection
of Intellectual Property in October of 1995.
</P>
<P>
Li Junhuan, an official with the General Administration of
Customs, said: "In most cases, Chinese Customs protects overseas
businesses' rights on our own initiative regardless of application
or not from them."
</P>
<P>
Besides the support from Customs, overseas businesses could
find protection for their advanced technologies through China's
patent system.
</P>
<P>
Patent applications from worldwide enterprises in China have
increased greatly in recent years, especially in the field of
high-tech industry. Some multinational businesses account for the
greatest part of China's total patent applications.
</P>
<P>
"In terms of the patent area, we have been very happy with the
progress in China," said Lois Boland, an official with the
U.S. Patent and Trademark Office, at an international forum in
April in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"We even got some anecdotal evidence from our companies
operating here in this respect," she said.
</P>
<P>
Gao Lulin, commissioner of the State Intellectual Property
Office, said: "To protect the intellectual property is to
safeguard all the creative achievements by humans."  
</P>
</TEXT>
