<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN to Reduce HIV Transmission From Mother to Child </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- United Nations agencies have
launched a new public health initiative designed to help
HIV-positive mothers increase their chances of having healthy
children.
</P>
<P>
At the 12th World AIDS Conference held in Geneva, the Joint
United Nations Program on HIV/AIDS (UNAIDS) announced on Monday it
would carry out pilot projects in some low-income countries in
Africa, Asia and Latin America where women have high rates of HIV
infection.
</P>
<P>
The projects would be worked together with the UN Children's
Fund (UNICEF) and the World Health Organization (WHO), the
organization said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The initiative aims to offer voluntary and confidential HIV
counseling and testing to pregnant women, and provide better birth
care and safe infant feeding methods for those who are affected by
anti-retroviral drugs.
</P>
<P>
Over the next 12-18 months, the joint initiative will seek to
support about 30,000 HIV-infected women in about 30 different
areas in some African countries such as Botswana, Burkina Faso,
Cambodia, Honduras, Rwanda, Zambia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
In Cote d'Ivoire, Tanzania, Thailand and Uganda, the
anti-retroviral drug trials for reducing mother-to-child
transmission have already been conducted.
</P>
<P>
Activities will start on a limited scale in the 11 pilot
countries and then expand through collaboration with other
governments, donor communities and the private sectors, the report
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
