<HEADLINE> History on England's Side against Argentina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Cao Li
</P>
<P>
SAINT-ETIENNE, France, June 29 (Xinhua) -- History will be on
England's side when they face South American heavy-weights Argentina
in a World Cup second-round game at Geoffroy-Guichard Stadium here on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
England have only lost twice to Argentina in the past 10
encounters, including their 2-1 defeat which featured an infamous
"Hand of God" goal by Diego Maradona in the quarterfinals of the 1986
World Cup in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
England coach Glenn Hoddle, despite playing down the media-hyped
element of revenge, still recalled that loss with a sour taste in the
mouth.
</P>
<P>
"I'd simply like to redress the balance - I'm still convinced that
Argentina wouldn't have won 2-1 without this golden hand-ball," said
Hoddle, who was in that squad who saw Maradona deflected the ball past
keeper Peter Shilton.
</P>
<P>
The younger generation of English footballers is not less
resentful, including midfielder Paul Scholes.
</P>
<P>
"Argentina is a painful memory for the Englishmen," said Manchester
United midfielder Scholes. "Personally, I admit I was upset by
Maradona's hand-ball in the 1986 World Cup."
</P>
<P>
Then he continued to indicate what Hoddle and all England players
worry most -- the deadly attacks from Argentina's Gabriel Batistuta,
who had scored four goals in three games.
</P>
<P>
"When we play Daniel Passarella's team we have to watch out for
Gabriel Batistuta's speed and ability to win the ball. However, when I
see the quality of our attackers, I'm very confident."
</P>
<P>
Liverpool's 18-year-old Michael Owen is almost definite to start up
front on the left alongside Newcastle United forward Alan Shearer on
the right.
</P>
<P>
Man United's David Beckham, who converted a superb free kick in
their 2-0 victory over Colombia, will be pulling all strings in
midfield.
</P>
<P>
Hoddle believed that his side is peaking at exactly the right time.
</P>
<P>
"We are feeling very good. I see no reason to think we can't beat
Argentina and go all the way," he said. "I think the players relish
this game and just can't wait for it. They are ready. But we will
respect them, not fear them."
</P>
<P>
On the other side, Argentines' common knowledge is that the English
defence is not as strong as theirs.
</P>
<P>
"England have strong points and good players. But they have a weak
point in defence -- they're strong in the air, but not on the ground
and we must exploit this," said midfielder Juan Veron.
</P>
<P>
However, Argentina themselves are less watertight in defence than
before, with defender Roberto Sensini doubtful for Tuesday due to a
thigh strain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980629.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Renminbi Will Not Devalue: Chinese Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 29 (Xinhua) -- A high-ranking Chinese official
said here Monday that China would not devalue its currency
Renminbi although the Asian financial crisis has put mounting
pressure on the country's exports.
</P>
<P>
Shi Guangsheng, Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation, reaffirmed the Chinese government's commitment when
he delivered a luncheon speech at the Hong Kong Economic Forum.
</P>
<P>
"The Renminbi will not devalue because this is necessary for
sustained economic development in China, and the long-term
prosperity and stability in Hong Kong," the trade minister told
the economic seminar.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the strong guarantee also "demonstrated
China's highly responsible attitude towards the economic and
financial stability in Asia as well as in the world."
</P>
<P>
"China is able to maintain the stability of the Renminbi," said
Shi, who backed his point with a string of encouraging facts: The
national economy continues to run smoothly towards the
eight-percent GDP growth target for 1998, plus hefty foreign
exchange reserves of above 140 billion U.S. dollars, and a sound
balance of international payment.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese official admitted that the Asian financial turmoil
has produced adverse effects on China's foreign trade, and even on
the whole economy. China's exports recorded a negative growth of
1.5 percent in May this year after 22-month consecutive increases,
due to big falls of exports to the ASEAN countries, Japan and
South Korea.
</P>
<P>
During the first five months of this year, China made an actual
use of foreign investment of 14.89 billion U.S. dollars, down 1.5
percent from the same period of 1997, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
In face of shock waves of the regional financial storm, the
Chinese government has taken initiatives to enlarge the domestic
demand by developing infrastructure projects, exploring the rural
market, and building houses for urban residents.
</P>
<P>
"These measures have produced, or are producing the desired
results," said Shi, who was optimistic that China can keep the
eight-percent economic growth this year, and at the same time curb
the inflation below three percent and maintain a stable currency.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Economic Forum, jointly organized by the Trade
Development Council (TDC) and the Hong Kong Policy Research
Institute, attracted some 1,000 participants to discuss a variety
of topics on Hong Kong's continued competitiveness, as well as the
regional and global economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
