<HEADLINE> Construction of Macao-Zhuhai Bridge Starts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Macao and neighboring Zhuhai
authorities in south China's Guangdong Province started on Monday
the construction of a bridge that connects the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The "Lotus Flower Bridge," named after the symbol on the flag
of the future Macao Special Administrative Region, will connect
Macao's Taipa Island and Zhuhai's Hengqin Island after 15 months
of construction.
</P>
<P>
The 1.3-kilometer-long bridge will open a second land crossing
apart from the current border gate to China's inland, when it
opens to traffic before the handover ceremony on December 20,
1999.
</P>
<P>
The two sides held a corner-stone laying ceremony on each side
of the bridge on Monday. They are to share the costs of the bridge
of 200 million patacas (about 25 million U.S. dollars). Macao will
be responsible for 82.8 million patacas (about 10.35 million
dollars) of the costs.
</P>
<P>
The bridge will have six traffic lanes. It will be 22 meters
high above water, and has a design traffic capacity of about 10
million vehicles a year. It is also near the Macao International
Airport and Macao's container terminal.
</P>
<P>
The bridge was first proposed last year by the Sino-Portuguese
Infrastructure Coordination Commission (SPICC), which decided the
financial construction earlier this month. Both Chinese and
Portuguese officials described the bridge as important for Macao
and Zhuhai.
</P>
<P>
"It will help improve Macao's outward land transportation
conditions and facilitate the development of Macao's islands and
Zhuhai's Hengqin Island," Xie Houhe, chief of SPICC Chinese
delegation, said earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
Jose Alves Paula, secretary for transportation and public
engineering, said at Monday's ceremony that the bridge will help
ease the pressure at the current border gate, and demonstrates the
friendly cooperation between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The SPICC is now considering some other infrastructure projects
concerning the two sides. Further discussions will be made on the
projects including the extension to Macao a Guangzhou-Zhuhai
railway.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
