<HEADLINE> Foreign Fund Managers Express Confidence in China's B-Share Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) - The prospect of China's economy and
its capital market will remain optimistic in spite of the negative
impact the Asian financial crisis has imposed on the country, some
foreign fund managers here said.
</P>
<P>
"We predict a good future for China and believe that a stable
and prosperous Chinese economy will help enliven the Asian
economy," Robert Scott, president of the Commercial General Union
(CGU), the biggest assurance group in the United Kingdom, said
today at a seminar on China Index Fund.
</P>
<P>
As one indication, the Commercial Union Assurance Group, one of
the predecessors of the CGU, launched the first China Index Fund
in January. The fund was listed in Ireland and channeled about 13
million U.S. dollars into China's B-share market.
</P>
<P>
It is also hailed by managers as the first index fund that
follows all the listed B shares on the two stock exchanges in
Shanghai and Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
China Index Fund, though already a main part of institutional
investors on worldwide stock markets, is an entirely new
investment means in China.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that China needs index funds since it does
long-term investing and does not trade so frequently to reduce
transaction costs, thereby providing stable and long-term funding
for the B-share market.
</P>
<P>
"That is why we launched the China Index Fund;, we mainly
intend to draw more and more foreign investors into the Chinese
stock market and therefore facilitate its stability and
prosperity," Scott said.
</P>
<P>
CGU currently manages a total of 100 billion British pounds of
assets, and is hailed as the biggest assurance group in the UK in
term of asset management.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
