<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Rescue Package Not Departs From Policy of Non- </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The latest package released by
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) government to
address the economic downturn does not depart from the
government's long-standing policy of non-interference with market
operations, a senior SAR official said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Officiating at the opening ceremony of the Hong Kong Economic
Forum, Financial Secretary Donald Tsang defended the rescue
package announced last Monday, saying, "We are just responding to
market conditions. Our aim is to facilitate economic adjustment,
not to tamper with normal market activities."
</P>
<P>
The measures were designed to ease the credit and liquidity
crunch, to stabilize property prices, to ease the cost burden to
families and businesses, and to help adapt to the economic
adjustment process generally for the next three quarters, Tsang
told some 1,000 participants of the seminar.
</P>
<P>
"We want to demonstrate once again that the HKSAR government
acts firmly and consistently and is alert and responsive to the
needs of the community," Tsang noted. The measures followed "our
largest-ever package of tax concessions, infrastructure investment
and public expenditure" secured in the 1998-1999 budget and a
package of seven measures announced at the end of May, he added.
</P>
<P>
In drawing up this latest package of measures, the government
is guided by four principles: maintain investors and international
community's confidence in Hong Kong, observe market discipline and
uphold prudent business practices, ensure no adverse impact on the
linked exchange rate system and uphold prudent management of
public finances.
</P>
<P>
"Adherence to these crucial principles for the Hong Kong
economy is of utmost importance," Tsang reiterated.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that the implementation of the package will worsen
the budget balance for the current financial year, turning an
estimated surplus of 10.7 billion HK dollars (1.4 billion U.S.
dollars) into an estimated deficit of 21.4 billion HK dollars (2.7
billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, Tsang stressed, "The deficit represents just 1.5
percent of the GDP for the year. Moreover, taking this deficit
with last year's surplus of 80.9 billion HK dollars (10.4 billion
U.S. dollars), the combined balance for two years is still well in
the positive."
</P>
<P>
Under the theme "Free Market Economy -- the Way Forward," the
two-day forum held just prior to the first anniversary of Hong
Kong's return to China will address free economy and other issues
of importance to Hong Kong's continued competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the forum will be more than 40 senior government
officials, think-tank members and business leaders from Hong Kong
and overseas, according to Paul Yip, chairman of the Hong Kong
Policy Research Institute, which organized the forum together with
the Hong Kong Trade Development Council.
</P>
<P>
Topics will cover Hong Kong as an international trade and
financial center, information and communications, human capital
development, the future of Hong Kong's industry, Asian values and
global partnership, the Asian economic crisis and the world
economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
