<DOCNO> XIE19980629.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Goodbye! Kai Tak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 29 (Xinhua) -- It was overcast with a few
showers last Saturday afternoon. On the side of the Olympic Avenue
outside Kai Tak Airport, two little girls, Kathy and Grace, were
taking photos for each other, with aircraft roaring overhead as
the backdrop.
</P>
<P>
The two teenagers were not alone. Around them were families,
lovers, tourists and well-equipped aircraft fans, who were seizing
the last chance to appreciate the beauty of huge iron birds flying
over the rooftop of low-rise blocks of urban Kowloon City.
</P>
<P>
All of them bore in mind that the scene will be gone in a few
days. To meet increasing aviation demands, the overcrowded Kai Tak
Airport will be replaced by a world-class new airport at Chek Lap
Kok, Lantau Island, on July 6.
</P>
<P>
The rooftop of the airport terminal building, a traditional
place to watch plane landing and taking off, was packed by people,
making the scene look like a carnival. Someone joked that
passengers would feel great as they were greeted or seen off by
such a big crowd they never enjoyed elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
People were bending over the railing, with eyes closely
following the aircraft -- appearing in the clouds in the west,
coming nearer and nearer, a beautiful turn-around over Kowloon
City, flying overhead and finally touching the runway. "You can
not see this elsewhere in the world, can you?" an old man said to
his friend.
</P>
<P>
The rooftop turned into a playground for kids. Some were posing
for a beautiful photo with a broad smile on the face while others
were chasing each other for fun. A mother was heard asking his two
boys: "Have you watched enough?"
</P>
<P>
An increasing number of policemen walked around to ensure the
safety of the mass of people never seen before.
</P>
<P>
Nearby, on Hau Wong Road, in the Kowloon Walled City Park, on
the waterfront of Kwun Tong, as well as on roofs of many Kowloon
City residential buildings, aircraft fans from Hong Kong itself
and overseas had their cameras adjusted to the sky day and night,
recording the fantastic scene which will never be seen in this
part of the territory again.
</P>
<P>
Actually, farewell to Kai Tak has been a hot topic in town
these days. Local TV stations presented special programs in memory
of Kai Tak, which has served Hong Kong people well for over 70
years and has witnessed the city's rising to economic prosperity
since the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
Print media gave full-page coverage to places where people can
get a good picture with aircraft in it.
</P>
<P>
Travel agents have been seizing the opportunity to promote
business. Special tours have been organized for departure from Kai
Tak and arrival at Chek Lap Kok and they are reported to have
obtained overwhelming response.
</P>
<P>
For 380,000 Kowloon City residents living under the flight
path, the relocation of the airport will free them from the noise
of the aircraft. But, during the last operational days of Kai Tak,
the long-awaited relief seems overwhelmed by a mixed feeling of
bidding farewell to part of their life.
</P>
<P>
Regal Airport Hotel, which has benefited for years from its
proximity to Kai Tak Airport, has planned a candlelight dinner on
the night of July 5 to say goodbye to Kai Tak, "one of the
greatest airports in the world." After the closure of the
airport, the hotel will renamed as Regal Kai Tak Hotel, to
commemorate the "old friend," while the name "Regal Airport Hotel"
will be given to its hotel at the new airport.
</P>
<P>
At the Kowloon City Plaza, the only large-scale shopping mall
in Kowloon City, a special exhibition featuring photos of various
phases of the airport has attracted many people.
</P>
<P>
And a party will be held on the rooftop of the plaza on the
night of July 5, the last day of the airport's operation, to bid
last farewell to Kai Tak. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980629.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 12:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Finds Footprints of Prehistoric Animals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Iranian experts have recently
discovered 40 footprints of prehistoric animals in Birjand in
northeastern Khorasan province, the official news agency IRNA
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted chancellor of Birjand University Mohammad
Hassan as saying that the oval-shaped footprints, discovered on
sedimentary rocks belonged to the third geological age 50 million
years ago.
</P>
<P>
Cultural heritage expert Hussein Aliabadi said the footprints
were left on a tiny layer of sediments when giant animals passed
the region, and the layer turned into rocks after millions
of years.
</P>
<P>
The marks were exposed as a result of erosion, he explained.
</P>
<P>
Aliabadi said that study showed a harmony among all the
footprints, with their measurements ranging from 48x26 to 12x8
centimeters.
</P>
<P>
This has led researchers to believe that the giant animals
belonged to one species and were moving from east to west in
groups.
</P>
<P>
And the giants are very likely to be one of the dinosaur
species, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980629.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Libraries Lack in Modern Information </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian libraries lack in
modern information equipment that are essential to the development of
science and technology.
</P>
<P>
Eight out of 20 regional libraries in the country do not have
television, computer and Internet and other modern equipment which are
used worldwide, said participants at a meeting of the Mbeya Library
Service Board over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
"Although the equipment are expensive, they are very essential for
providing up-to-date information to the people," The Guardian
Monday quoted Mbeya Chief Librarian Emanuel Lubanda, as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Lubanda cited regions without such equipment as Mbeya, Dodoma,
Rukwa and Coast.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Lubanda has called on libraries not to rely heavily on
donated books, saying that dependence on donated books will
undermine Tanzania's culture.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out that most of the donated books were outdated
as they were printed in 1960s and 1970s.
</P>
<P>
Mbeya Library Service Board chairman, Robert Chidosa, called on
people to cultivate a habit of reading, which is ignored by most
adults in the country. 
</P>
