<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan PM Meets U.S. Senators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif
Monday expressed the hope that the United States would play a
leading role in initiating a credible process to promote Pak-India
dialogue and resolve the grave security crisis in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with visiting U.S. Senators Sam Brownback and
Charles Robb, Sharif thanked them for playing their role in the
U.S. Senate and appreciated the greater understanding in the U.S.
Congress for Pakistan's security concerns and the need to resolve
the core issue of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
"Unless the Kashmir issue is resolved, peace and security
cannot be ensured in the region," Sharif stressed.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release by the Foreign Ministry, the two
senators briefed Sharif about the U.S. position on imposition of
sanctions, promotion of global non-proliferation and the need to
restore peace and stability in South Asia, by resolving the
underlying causes of tensions.
</P>
<P>
They also spoke of the steps that had been initiated in the
U.S. Senate regarding the provision of discretionary powers and
flexibility to the President on imposition of sanctions on the
basis of national interest.
</P>
<P>
They also referred to the Senate resolution on Kashmir,
currently under consideration, which underlines the importance of
resolving the Kashmir dispute that had become a nuclear
flash-point endangering regional peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
The senators agreed that the resolution of the Kashmir dispute
was central to peace and stability in the region, and urged
Pakistan to be more responsive to the non-proliferation regime
that may help in the early lifting of the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, the two senators had a meeting with Foreign
Minister Gohar Ayub Khan. The meeting covered most of the issues
raised with Prime Minister Sharif, but in greater detail, the
press release said.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Afghanistan was also discussed in the context
of regional peace and security. The two sides also stressed the
need for removing the irritants that had cropped up and for
further enhancing the bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to maintain a regular contact to create a greater
understanding of each other's position.
</P>
<P>
The two senators, who arrived here Sunday night, are the first
American officials to visit Islamabad since Pakistan's detonation
of nuclear devices at the end of May. They also heard a briefing
on the situation in Indian-held Kashmir, particularly along the
Line of Control (LOC), of which they had a tour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
