<HEADLINE> Commonwealth Official in Nigeria for Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Commonwealth Secretary-General
Emeka Anyaoku will hold talks with Nigeria's new leader, General
Abdulsalam Abubakar Monday in capital Abuja on relations between
his organization and Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Anyaoku, who arrived at the Lagos airport Sunday afternoon,
told the press that it believed that Abubakar's commitment
to the democratization and release of political detainees will
pave the way for Nigeria's return to the international community.
</P>
<P>
"The Commonwealth and the international community had welcomed
General Abubakar's inaugural statement and the steps he has taken
so far," Anyaoku said.
</P>
<P>
"My hope is that this is the beginning and my presence is the
beginning of the process of Nigeria's re-integration into the
international community," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the Nigerian-Commonwealth relation, he said he is
optimistic that the suspension of Nigeria's membership may soon
be reviewed.
</P>
<P>
On what it would take for Nigeria to fully regain its position
in the Commonwealth, Anyaoku said the disposition of the
incumbent military regime to ensure democratization, national
reconciliation and adherence to fundamental human rights would
guarantee that.
</P>
<P>
"I think the extent to which the new government has gone in
dealing with those concerns, is a good ground for hope that the
process will lead to normalization of Nigeria's relationship with
the Commonwealth," he said.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria was suspended from the Commonwealth in November 1995
following the execution of Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight other leaders
of the Movement for the Survival of Ogoni People on charges of
murder. 
</P>
