<HEADLINE> General Electric Signs $160 Million Deal With China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- General Electric (GE) Inc. of the
United States today signed a contract worth 160 million
U.S. dollars with the Shandong Huaneng Power Development Corp. to
provide key equipment for the Dezhou Power Plant in east China's
Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
This is another major deal between GE and China. The two sides
have signed 10 memorandums of understanding (MOU), or letters of
intent (LOI), for future cooperation in the last two months, said
Goran S. Malm, senior vice-president of GE and president of GE
Asia Pacific.
</P>
<P>
According to the contract, the GE Power System will supply an
integrated steam turbine system, including a broad range of
equipment and services for two 660,000-kilowatt generators at the
Dezhou Power Plant.
</P>
<P>
At the Great Hall of the People today, Chinese and
U.S. companies signed seven cooperation agreements or contracts
valued at 2.1 billion U.S. dollars. The GE contract was one of the
seven.
</P>
<P>
In August of 1994, Shandong Huaneng became China's first
state-owned power company to be listed on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
GE's Malm, who came from Hong Kong to attend today's
contract-signing ceremony, said in an interview with Xinhua:
"the Dezhou project and the other 10 MOUs or LOIs further
demonstrate GE's long-term commitment to invest in China."
</P>
<P>
Malm said he planned to tour several Chinese cities this autumn
to investigate the investment environment in an effort to find
new cooperative opportunities.
</P>
<P>
He said the 10 projects, each involving millions of dollars,
covers GE-Chinese technological cooperation or production
cooperation in Liaoning, Shaanxi and Fujian provinces and the
cities of Beijing and Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
GE has opened 18 offices and established 24 joint ventures or
solely-funded enterprises in China. Its investment in China
has exceeded one billion dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
