<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Tries Again to Squeeze Palestinians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu on Monday tried again to squeeze the Palestinians,
saying that if they implement their commitments, a peace agreement
would be reached in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after his meeting with his Spanish
counterpart Jose Maria Aznar on Monday, Netanyahu said that "peace
is very, very close if the Palestinians do their part."
</P>
<P>
"Peace is based on reciprocity," he said, demanding the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) must fulfill its commitments
to the security of Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks have been stalled for more
than one year over Israel's intransigent settlement policy and the
long-delayed second stage troop withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
However, Netanyahu has repeatedly managed to shift the blame on
the Palestinians. He said earlier that the Palestinians will
determine the fate of the process and the negotiations between two
sides over the second Israeli redeployment could be concluded next
month.
</P>
<P>
Israeli government is under growing pressure from the United
States and the PNA to accept a peace initiative, according to
which Israel would hand over 13 percent more of the West Bank to
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu also reiterated at the news conference that to hold
another international peace conference in Madrid like the one
seven years ago is a "good idea" to push forward the Middle East
peace process.
</P>
<P>
He said that the multilateral conference would only complement
the bilateral negotiations between Israel and its Arab neighbors,
not replace them.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Aznar said that Spain is ready to make "positive
contributions" to the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Netanyahu idea has already been rejected by the PNA, which
called it another ploy by the hardline Israeli prime minister to
retard any progress in the dying peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
