<HEADLINE> UN Commission Handles First Claims Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Governing Council of the United
Nations Compensation Commission (UNCC) began its 28th session here
Monday to consider the first instalment of corporate claims
involving four large corporates.
</P>
<P>
But the UN commission did not reveal the names of the four
companies which have sought a total of more than two billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The UNCC was established in accordance with UN Security Council
resolutions 687 and 692 (1991) to pay compensation for losses and
damages suffered by individuals, corporations, governments and
international organizations as a direct result of Iraq's invasion
and occupation of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
During its three-day session, the commission will also consider
the appointment of two new panels of commissioners to address
corporate and government claims against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
It will consider the sixth instalment of individual claims for
damages of up to 100,000 dollars involving 71,042 claims filed by
74 governments and three international organizations.
</P>
<P>
Funds to pay compensation are drawn from the Compensation
Fund, also established under Security Council resolution 692.
</P>
<P>
The fund receives up to 30 percent of the revenue from the
export of Iraqi oil under the "oil-for-food" mechanism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
