<HEADLINE> Uganda Loses $70m to Graft: report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Some 70 million U.S. Dollars or 7.6
percent of the Uganda's government expenditure were missing from the
public coffers in the 1997/98 financial year due to graft, a report
has said.
</P>
<P>
Unaccounted expenditures, incorrect spendings and unauthorized
cash withdrawals are held mainly responsible for the loss of the
money, the East African weekly quoted Uganda's auditor-general's
annual report as saying Monday.
</P>
<P>
This report is regarded as best indicator of corruption in the
government departments of the east African country.
</P>
<P>
The total government expenditure in this fiscal year which will
end this month is 913.4 million Dollars. And a considerable amount
of the money is donated by other countries.
</P>
<P>
As a response to the rampant corruption among government officials,
major donors including Denmark and Japan demand accountability and
refund of their donations.
</P>
<P>
Denmark contributed 46 million Dollars in direct aid to Uganda in
1997, excluding aid channeled through non-governmental organizations.
</P>
<P>
Japan gives Uganda between 3.7 and 4.8 million Dollars of aid
annually in chemicals, agricultural inputs and road construction
equipment.
</P>
<P>
Foreign aid to Uganda totaled some 450 million Dollars in 1997
and its foreign debt is approaching 4 billion Dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
