<HEADLINE> S. African Opposition Attacks Plans to Establish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 29 (Xinhua) -- South African opposition
parties have strongly attacked government's plans to forge
diplomatic relations with Iraq, Business Day paper reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo said earlier this month that the
issue of establishing ties with Iraq was under discussion.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the discussions will be finalized soon so that
the necessary steps to establish diplomatic relations with Iraq
can be taken," he said in a response to a parliamentary question.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Foreign Minister Aziz Pahad was in Kuwait Sunday for
talks with the Kuwaiti government. It was understood that the
issue of full diplomatic relations between South Africa and the
Saddam Hussein government was on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
A Democratic Party (DP) spokesman, James Selfe, said Sunday
that by all reliable accounts Iraq's human rights record was
appalling, and even in the darkest days of apartheid South Africa
had not been as bad as Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The National Party (NP), the biggest opposition party in the
country, also criticized the plan. NP member of parliament Boy
Geldenhuys said Sunday that with Iraq at loggerheads with the
United Nations (UN) over weapons inspections, the time was not
right to establish ties with the middle eastern country.
</P>
<P>
Geldenhuys said that it did not appear that the government
decision was prompted by trade concerns, as South Africa has just
closed down important missions in California, the United States,
and in Brussels, Belgium. It made no sense to close these
missions in favor of Iraq, he added.
</P>
<P>
Responding the criticism, Foreign Affairs spokesman Marco Boni
said Sunday the talks about diplomatic ties with Iraq should be
seen against the background of the Non-Aligned Movement.
</P>
<P>
He said South Africa, which will host the movement's summit in
late August and take over its chair, is considering normalizing
relations with all the movement's members, of which Iraq is one.
</P>
</TEXT>
