<HEADLINE> British Paper Details Libyan Arms Deal With S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 29 (Xinhua) -- A British newspaper Sunday
again insisted on the truth of its report that South Africa and
Libya have stricken a secret arms-for-oil deal, South African
media reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The London-based Sunday Telegraph provoked an angry reaction
from the South African government last week when it first made
its allegations that a 500-million-U.S. Dollar deal had been
reached, in defiance of UN sanctions against Tripoli.
</P>
<P>
Mandela's office dismissed the report as "a complete
fabrication."
</P>
<P>
But in this week's edition, the paper said it had now learned
that the deal was finally concluded during two stopovers Mandela
made in Tripoli on his way to and from last October's
Commonwealth summit meeting in Edinburg, Britain.
</P>
<P>
It said that earlier last year, Musa Kusa, head of foreign
security in the Libyan intelligence service, had made two
clandestine trips to South Africa to discuss the proposed deal.
</P>
<P>
This had led it to conclude that "there seems no doubt that
members of the South African intelligence services have
negotiated a deal to supply the Libyans with arms and military
spare parts in return for the Libyans providing cut-price oil."
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the South African military equipment
would be sent to Libya "through private individuals and companies
with close connections to the South African military
establishment," according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
South Africa Sunday criticized the newspaper report again,
saying the publication should be ashamed of its reports.
</P>
<P>
"This second report proves more than before that their earlier
story was a fabrication and a lie. They should be ashamed of
themselves," said Mandela's spokesman, Parks Mankahlana.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Britain, which are at the center of an
international standoff with Libya over Lockerbie bombing, have
accepted South Africa's denial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
