<DOCNO> XIE19980629.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Official: Loose Monetary Policy Has Drawbacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 29 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Treasury Secretary
Robert Rubin said here Monday that the adoption of a loose
monetary policy by a country experiencing an economic downturn
could lead to a substantial depreciation of its currency and
additional inflation.
</P>
<P>
It will also deter foreign investments, encourage capital
flight and intensify debt repayment risks for loans denominated in
foreign currencies, he said at a press conference at the end of
his two-day visit here.
</P>
<P>
He agreed to the view that a tight monetary policy may strangle
an economy, but said that a loose policy has its drawbacks too.
</P>
<P>
In a clear defense of the International Monetary Fund (IMF)'s
prescription of high interest rates and credit squeeze for
economic reform, Rubin said what the IMF has done is about right.
</P>
<P>
He said that the IMF was trying to find the right balance in
the monetary policy and that is why no "one formula fits all
approach."
</P>
<P>
In regard of Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad's view
that the IMF's strategy on interest rates adopted by Malaysia has
damaged the economy, Rubin said, "I think the Prime Minister's
views on a lot of issues are fairly well known. I guess it is fair
to say that the U.S.' views are fairly well known too."
</P>
<P>
Rubin, however, felt that Malaysia's interest rate policy
should be determined by its own authorities.
</P>
<P>
On feedback from U.S. businessmen operating in Malaysia, he
said they are still confident of Malaysia's underlying strength
and are convinced that their investments in this country would
continue.
</P>
<P>
On his visit here, Rubin said he has had good discussions with
Malaysian leaders and that it was "time exceedingly well spent."
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Rubin called on Mahathir, held talks with
Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister and Finance Minister Anwar Ibrahim
and attended a closed-door dialogue on "Responding To The Asian
Crisis", which was also attended by Anwar and Malaysia's senior
government officials and leading local corporate figures.
</P>
<P>
Rubin arrived here Sunday for a two-day visit to Malaysia as
part of his second tour to the economically-troubled Asia-Pacific
region. He will also visit Thailand and South Korea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
