<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Revokes World Status of 16 Airports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 29 (Xinhua) -- In a major crackdown on the
massive movement of illegal goods across South Africa's borders,
the government has revoked the international status of 16
airports.
</P>
<P>
This leaves about 40 airports which are licensed to handle the
movement of international traffic, The Citizen paper reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
At the weekend, the National Inter-departmental Structure for
Border Control (Nids), which comprises officials from the Home
Affairs Department, the border police and the South African
Revenue Service (Sars), said the move was in compliance with
international practice.
</P>
<P>
It said international airports would have to comply with
specific criteria to ensure efficient cross-border movement of
personnel and goods, and duty collection, to curb cross-border
crimes and detect contraband.
</P>
<P>
Sars Deputy Director H Tripmaker said last week that illegal
goods across South Africa's borders was estimated at 17 billion
Rand (3.1 billion U.S. Dollars) a year.
</P>
<P>
She said the illegal flow of aliens and goods has an extremely
negative impact on the country's economy and crime rate.
</P>
<P>
Last year the government announced its intention to restrict
the number of international airports to only 10. It also wants to
reduce the 52 land border posts to 19 and the number of seaports
for international freight to seven.
</P>
<P>
There are an estimated 550 airstrips in South Africa, of which
192 are being licensed as airports with the Transport Department.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
