<HEADLINE> Malaysia Says Crisis Not to Deter Liberalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The present economic crisis
will not deter Malaysia's ongoing efforts to deregulate and
liberalize its economy, Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister Anwar
Ibrahim said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Anwar, who is also the finance minister, said Malaysia is
dedicated to reforming the economy to face the challenges of
globalization which is unstoppable and irreversible.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the inherent and destabilizing risks of large
and volatile capital flows could be managed and minimized if the
process of deregulation and liberalization is judiciously
sequenced," he said in his opening address at a roundtable
discussion with U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert E. Rubin here.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said that to minimize shock and financial instability,
the progress of deregulation and liberalization must take into
account the modernization of the financial sector and the
establishment of an appropriate regulatory framework.
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysia was pleased that the United States was
spearheading the move towards a new architecture for the
international monetary system that would manage and resolve, if
not prevent, future crises.
</P>
<P>
"To prevent future crises we require greater surveillance of
the international financial markets and capital flows. We demand
transparency and disclosure in domestic finance and we expect
nothing less in the international system," Anwar said.
</P>
<P>
He said there is also a need to coordinate information-sharing
between national regulators, especially among those with
supervisory insight into the institutions operating in major
financial centers including offshore centers.
</P>
<P>
Anwar held that global cooperation between national regulators
and regular contact between the regulators and the operators of
leverage funds are absolutely necessary in ensuring the stability
of the international monetary system.
</P>
<P>
On measures to cushion the impact of the contagion economic
crisis, he said Malaysia has taken firm preemptive measures such
as mergers in the banking system and other administrative measures
to enhance resilience and transparency.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the banking system still suffered from
insufficient liquidity as a result of the outflow of short-term
capital.
</P>
<P>
"The interest rates, although lower than in the rest of the
region, are already prohibitively high, thus raising the cost of
doing business in this country," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said the government had recently announced a
counter-cyclical package to pump-prime the economy and stimulate
growth.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. was the largest source of foreign direct investment
(FDI) in Malaysia last year with 684.9 million U.S. dollars of
capital investments in 39 projects approved.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is Malaysia's largest trading partner with a trade
volume of 20.095 billion dollars in 1997, which was 17.7 percent
of Malaysia's total trade in that year. For the first four months
of this year, trade between the U.S. and Malaysia amounted to
9.837 billion dollars, or 21.3 percent of Malaysia's global trade
during that period.
</P>
<P>
The roundtable discussion on "Responding to the Asian Crisis"
was jointly organized by the Finance Ministry, the Institute of
Strategy and International Studies of Malaysia (ISIS) and the
Oxford and Cambridge Club of Malaysia. Senior government officials
and local corporate leaders attended the discussion.
</P>
<P>
Rubin arrived here Sunday for a two-day visit for talks with
Malaysian leaders, as part of his second tour of the
economically-troubled Asia-Pacific region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
