<HEADLINE> Restructuring of Financial Institutions in South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 29 (Xinhua) -- South Korea said Monday that its
five non-viable banks will be merged by five well-managed banks.
</P>
<P>
The five sick banks -- Daedong, Dongnam, Dongwha, Kyungki and
Chungchong -- will be respectively taken over by Kookmin, Housing
and Commercial, Shinhan, KorAm and Hana, said the Financial
Supervisory Commission Monday.
</P>
<P>
The five sound banks will take over their assets and
liabilities under a "purchase and assumption" formula.
</P>
<P>
The selection of the five sick banks came from the commission's
evaluation of a list of 12 banks which had failed to meet a
8-percent of minimum capital adequacy ratio set by the South
Korean government.
</P>
<P>
The remaining seven of the 12 banks are also required to take
measures to improve their operation and management under the
government's demands before 1999.
</P>
<P>
The government has vowed to take tough measures against
non-viable banks, which included shutdowns, transfer of businesses
to sound banks, and forced mergers and acquisition.
</P>
<P>
The decision is reportedly in line with preconditions attached
to an agreement signed between the government and the
International Monetary Fund last December for a rescue loan of 57
billion U.S. dollars to help recover South Korea's crisis-ridden
economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
