<HEADLINE> G. Bissau Seeks ECOMOG Intevention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 29 (Xinhua) -- President Joau Bernardo Vieira of Guinea
Bissau has called for the intervention of the west African
peacekeeping force ECOMOG into the situation in his country, the News
Agency of Nigeria reported.
</P>
<P>
The president was seeking assistance from the sub-regional body,
Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) in the battle to
overcome a two-week-old rebellion by some of the country's soldiers,
sources at the ECOWAS secretariat in Abuja, capital of Nigeria, said
over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Chiefs of staff of the organization will meet in Abidjan, Cote
d'Ivoire, to look at the rebellion and consider the possibility of
intervention.
</P>
<P>
Guinea Bissau's former Army Chief of Staff Amsumane Mane led the
rebellion shortly after his sacking on June 6.
</P>
<P>
The country's neighbors, Guinea and Senegal have sent some 2,000
troops to help the Vieira government' efforts to end the revolt that
has killed an unknown number of people in the country.
</P>
<P>
The one-day meeting of chiefs of staff, scheduled for Tuesday, is
expected to make recommendations to the defense and foreign ministers
from west Africa, who will meet on the issue and will also make
recommendations to their respective heads of state.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is coming on the heels of consultive visits to Senegal,
Gambia and Guinea by ECOWAS Executive Secretary Lansana Kouyate,
according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
They explained that the consultation and the meetings were meant to
generate a consensus for sub-regional action in favor of President
Vieira.
</P>
<P>
Liberia's President Charles Taylor last week appealed to West
African leaders to intervene militarily through ECOMOG to restore
peace in Guinea Bissau.
</P>
<P>
"A collective regional initiative is necessary to buttress the
current efforts of Guinea and Senegal in Bissau," Taylor said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG was sent to Liberia in 1990 and succeeded in ending
Liberia's civil war in 1997, which paved way for Taylor to become the
country's post-war president.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, the sub-regional force also helped restore the
elected government of President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah in Sierra Leone
after it expelled the military junta of Paul Johnny Koromah that
seized power in a coup in May last year.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG is stepping up its opeartions in eastern and northern Sierra
Leone for an early mop-up of remnants of the junta and allied rebels.
</P>
<P>
Currently, fighting in Guinea Bissau has centered on a big military
complex in the Bra district of the capital Bissau and on the airport.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
