<HEADLINE> Uganda's Agriculture Ministry to Be Cut by 3/4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's Ministry of Agriculture
will sack a substantial number of its staff in the ministry's coming
streamlining program, a senior official has said.
</P>
<P>
Israel Kibirige Ssebunya, the State Minister for Agriculture,
said this while launching an agricultural program over the weekend,
the Monitor paper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Out of the 1,200 people, only 281 are going to stay," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The ministry will now only evolve strategic plans, coordinate,
monitor and evaluate activities and disseminate new technologies,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
In a recent reshuffle of government bodies, the number of
ministries in the country was reduced to 17 from 21 and some 30,000
civil servants are expected to be laid off.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has about 300,000 civil servants and it is considered a
too big size for the country's economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
