<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Committed to Asia's Economic Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The United States is
committed to any economic reform undertaken by Asian countries to
resolve the economic crisis, U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert E.
Rubin said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We know that the Asian region has the enormous underlying
strength to deal with its economic crisis. However, it requires
recognition of problems and changes (to resolve the crisis)," he
said in his opening address at a roundtable discussion with
Malaysia's senior government officials and leading local corporate
figures here.
</P>
<P>
He told the discussion themed "Responding to the Asian crisis"
that the U.S. believes that the economic crisis could only be
resolved by working together.
</P>
<P>
"There will be a difficult time ahead but there are some signs
of progress as well," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that in the case of Malaysia, the country is not far
from resolving its economic problems based on its strong
willingness to follow all measures being aimed at the crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said that Malaysia has been shielded from the "worst
conditions because of a better supervision system."
</P>
<P>
However, Rubin said that on the whole, Asia still has a long
way to go (in overcoming the economic crisis) especially in
restoring investors' confidence.
</P>
<P>
Citing the lack of transparency as one of the contributory
factors of the regional economic crisis, Rubin suggested five
measures to overcome these economic problems.
</P>
<P>
He said firstly, Asian economists should look into the matter
of reducing restriction on foreign ownership; secondly, financial
institutions should be required to give credit extension on a
purely commercial basis; thirdly, mergers or bailouts should be
conducted on a transparent basis; the fourth, an effective social
"safety net" should be established; and the fifth is to maintain a
sound fiscal and monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
He said all these measures are difficult to carry out but the
best is "to recognize the economic problems."
</P>
<P>
He also said that the U.S. is deeply concerned with the
Japanese economy as the decline of the yen has reflected on the
economic condition of the whole of the Asian region.
</P>
<P>
He said that problems concerning the Japanese banking system
need to be addressed effectively for the benefit of the Asian
region.
</P>
<P>
Rubin arrived here Sunday for a two-day visit for talks with
Malaysian leaders, as part of his second tour to the
economically-troubled Asia-Pacific region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
