<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Stock Market Largely Quiet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Share prices dipped a bit Monday
on the Singapore Market ahead of the much anticipated off-budget
measures to boost the economy, which the government just announced
at 17:00 local time (09:00 GMT).
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Industrials Index (STII) shed 0.44
points to close at 1,085.15 points.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the Singapore dollar's afternoon fall, fueled by
the Malaysian ringgit's plunge, has almost soured investment
sentiment.
</P>
<P>
Shares relinquished early gains as excitement ahead of the
off-budget measures, which are aimed at softening the impact of
the turmoil rocking Asia, wore off.
</P>
<P>
The total volume was down to 115.83 million shares, valued at
203.19 million Singapore dollars (118.82 million U.S. dollars).
There were 177 losers against 92 gainers with 319 stocks remained
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
DBS Land was the most active stock as it registered 9.07
million shares traded. It was followed by Wing T which had 6.56
million units traded. SingTel was next with 6.53 million shares
changing hands.
</P>
<P>
Parkway was the top gainer of the day as it increased by 22
cents to close at 2.92 Singapore dollars. SPH finished 20 cents up
to 12.00 Singapore dollars. Parkway W90 increased by 15.5 cents to
end at 0.975 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Creative 50 remained the biggest loser as it
lost 80 cents to finish at 20.50 Singapore dollars. CityDev fell
by 22 cents to finish at 4.48 Singapore dollars. Bukit Sem lost 20
cents to end at 7.80 Singapore dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
