<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's HIV Cases on Rise: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 29 (Xinhua) -- There has been a sharp increase
in number of HIV-AIDS cases all over the country, said a national
survey available here Monday by India's Ministry of Health and
Family Welfare.
</P>
<P>
The situation in the country's States like Maharashtra, Andhra
Pradesh, Manipur and Karnataka is alarming. In Andhra Pradesh, for
instance, out of 700 people tested at clinics for sexually
transmitted diseases, 158 tested HIV positive, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
The survey has also expressed concern over the AIDS situation
in Maharashtra State of southwestern India. The percentage of HIV
positive cases have sharply increased in this State in the last
four years. When the survey was last done in 1994, the prevalence
of HIV-AIDS was five percent and this figure has now gone up to
8.8-20 percent.
</P>
<P>
The situation in other northeastern States is no better. The
health officials believe that the main cause of the rising cases
in this region was the drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
The national survey was conducted by the National AIDS Control
Organization (NACO) under the aegis of the Ministry of Health and
Family Welfare during February-March this year. The health
officials had selected 151 sites in the country as established by
international rules for carrying out surveys. Over 36,218 samples
were taken from all over the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980629.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany's Steel Output Growing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Germany's crude steel production rose
by 8.2 percent in the first five months this year to 19.7 million
tons amidst an upward trend in the national economy.
</P>
<P>
The output of hot-rolled steel products also jumped by 12.7
percent to 16.66 million tons, and pig iron output rose by 8.9
percent to reach 13.62 million tons, the Federal Statistics Office
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Germany's gross domestic product (GDP) is expected to grow by
2.6 percent this year after a 2.2 percent rise in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
