<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nothing-to-Lose Attitude to Help Mexicans: Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTPELLIER, France, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Mexicans will be
helped by a nothing-to-lose attitude going into their World Cup second
round game against Germany, coach Manuel Lapuente said.
</P>
<P>
"We came here with a lot of faith in ourselves. We're doing our
best and have nothing to prove," said Lapuente late on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The coach hinted that his team would take a more aggressive way in
Monday's game here, saying "It would be too dangerous for us to stay
on the defensive against the Germans."
</P>
<P>
Lapuente claimed he knew two or three, if not all, secrets of the
European champions Germany.
</P>
<P>
"Their defence is solid, their two forwards (Oliver) Bierhoff and
(Juergen) Klinsmann are very good. Lothar Matthaus will definitely
play, with Olaf Thon alongside," he said.
</P>
<P>
Lapuente had said earlier that he had information on their second
round foes through German trainer Axel Bierbaum who he worked with
when he first began coaching in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
"I know all about German football from him," Lapuente had said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
