<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stock Prices Rise For 4th Straight Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices in Tokyo rose for the
4th consecutive day Monday, boosted by last Friday's merger news
regarding the Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan (LTCB).
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange were up 155.69 points, or 1.02
percent, from last Friday's closing of 15,365.73.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, gained 11.40 points, or 0.96 percent, to
1,202.22.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei has surged more than 300 points over the past four
trading days with Monday's rise being the biggest single-day gain.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the First Section was estimated at 400 million
shares, down from 424.95 million last Friday.
</P>
<P>
LTCB, the day's most actively traded issue, was bolstered by
the news of a possible merger of LTCB, Japan's second largest
credit bank, and the Sumitomo Trust and Banking Co.
</P>
<P>
The banking marriage, if go ahead, would create the country's
largest bank, with 42 trillion yen (296 billion U.S. dollars) in
assets.
</P>
<P>
The merger news, which had given last friday's stocks a sudden
boost, and relatively relaxed currency trading in the morning,
encouraged investors Monday, but traders said much of the buying
was simply covering of short-selling positions.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,334 issues listed on the First Section, gainers
outnumbered losers 791 to 299, with 169 issues remaining
unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
