<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading British Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading British newspapers Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Times:
</P>
<P>
-- An extra 1,000 troops have been drafted into Northern
Ireland to contain any violence that could follow an announcement
Monday about the re-routing of next Sunday's hugely-contentious
Drumcree parade.
</P>
<P>
Financial Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Japan's ruling Liberal Democratic party Sunday stepped up
efforts to tackle the country's economic problems, pledging a
rapid decision on a proposed "bridge bank" to take over loans of
failed institutions.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Telegraph:
</P>
<P>
-- The calm following the storm known as El Nino is about to be
shattered. Meteorologists said that La Nina, or Little Girl, will
strike later this year and bring with it storms, torrential
downpours and bitterly cold weather.
</P>
<P>
The Independent:
</P>
<P>
-- The new political shape of Ulster has finally emerged, with
former enemies set to share seats in the province's new
government. The assembly will elect the cabinet, and David
Trimble, of the Ulster Unionist Party, is expected to become first
minister.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian:
</P>
<P>
-- The British government will attempt to repair its badly
damaged relationship with Rupert Murdoch when Chancellor Gordon
Brown delivers a keynote speech at a conference next month of the
media tycoon's top editors and executives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
