<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, U.S. Sign Contracts, Agreements (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- China and the United States held a
grand ceremony for the signing of seven contracts and cooperative
agreements worth nearly 2 billion U.S. dollars today at the Great
Hall of the People.
</P>
<P>
So far the relevant companies of the two countries have signed
12 significant contracts and agreements in the last week, worth
nearly 3 billion dollars, besides the five inked between June 22
and 26.
</P>
<P>
These 12 projects worth a total of 2.2 billion dollars for
purchasing U.S.-made products in various cooperation modes in the
fields of aviation, energy, chemical fertilizers, environmental
protection, telecommunications, computers and automobiles.
</P>
<P>
The seven contracts and agreements signed today are:
</P>
<P>
-- Contracts and agreements of intent between the Civil
Aviation Administration of China and the Boeing Company for the
purchase of 27 Boeing aircrafts with a value of 1.2 billion
dollars, including formal contracts for 17 aircrafts worth 800
million dollars and agreements of intent for 10 B-737 worth 400
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
-- A contract on the purchase of 161.7 million dollars worth of
turbine islands for the 3rd phase of the Dezhou Power Plant in
Shandong Province by China Huaneng Group and General Electric Co.
</P>
<P>
-- A contract on Sinochem importing 2 million tons of DAP worth
400 million dollars from the U.S. Phoschem, Cargill and Hydro
Farmland.
</P>
<P>
-- A letter of intent on urban air-quality monitoring project
between China's State General Administration of Environmental
Protection and the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency.
</P>
<P>
-- A contract for the purchase of automatic air-quality
monitoring equipment by China's State General Administration of
Environmental Protection from the U.S. Dasibi Company. The
5-million-dollar worth equipment will be used in 11 Chinese cities
for automatic air quality monitoring.
</P>
<P>
-- A contract for prospecting for coal bed methane (CBM)
between China CBM Company, the U.S.'s ARCO and Phillips, involving
30 million dollars of investment.
</P>
<P>
-- A contract between China Great Wall Computer Group and IBM
China Company Limited on an investment increase of 76.85 million
dollars for a joint venture.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980629.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, U.S. Sign Contracts, Agreements  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chinese State Councillor Wu Yi, Minister in charge of the State
Development Planning Commission Zeng Peiyan, and U.S Secretary of
Commerce William Daley were among those Chinese and U.S. officials
attending the signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
According to the State Development Planning Commission, the
contracts and agreements signed in the last week will not only
help increase Sino-U.S. economic and trade ties, but also
demonstrate broad prospects for mutually-beneficial and
complementary economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Since China and the U.S. forged diplomatic ties in 1979,
economic cooperation has been developing rapidly.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Customs statistics show Sino-U.S. trade volume in 1997
reached 49 billion U.s. dollars, 20 times the 1979 figure.
</P>
<P>
China is the second largest trade partner of the United States,
whereas the U.S. is China's fourth largest.
</P>
<P>
By May, the U.S.-funded projects in China stood at 25,184, with
contractual investment of 41.54 billion dollars and in-paid
investment of 18.74 billion dollars, according to statistics.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, U.S. banks have opened 10 branches in China, and U.S.
insurers with three in this country.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Minister of Information Industry Wu Jichuan and
Governor of the People's Bank of China Dai Xianglong met with
Daley on separative occasions today.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980629.0151 </DOCNO>
