<HEADLINE> First Contact Between U.S., KLA Confirmed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Chief U.S. negotiator for the
Kosovo crisis Richard Holbrooke confirmed Sunday that Washington
had held its first official talks with the Kosovo Liberation Army
(KLA), Yugoslav news agency Tanjug reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the sidelines of a political and economic forum in
Kran Montana, Switzerland, Holbrooke said the first official
contact took place Friday between the U.S. special envoy for
former Yugoslavia, Robert Gelbard, and representatives of the KLA
whom he refused to identify.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke said Ethnic Albanian political leader Ivrahim Rugova,
a non-violence advocator in seeking Kosovo's independence, knew of
the contacts in advance and supported them.
</P>
<P>
Continuation of the contact would depend on whether the KLA
could control the military forces on ground, Holbrooke added.
</P>
<P>
During his Kosovo visit last Wednesday, Holbrooke himself had
an "occasional and brief talk" with members of the KLA.
</P>
<P>
According to Western estimates, the KLA has seized at least
one-third of the land in Kosovo. The army, composed of Albanian
militants, were reportedly outlawed by Belgrade as a terrorist
group.
</P>
<P>
At least 300 people have died in fighting since February
between Serb forces and the KLA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
