over 1,500 others, according to the Red Crescent officials.
</P>
<P>
Cumhuriyet (Republic):
</P>
<P>
-- A survey published by the Plar-Gallup Research Company has
indicated that Turkish business circles are dissatisfied with the
country's economic situation.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-seven percent of the surveyed dubbed the on-going
economy "bad," while 10.9 percent found it "very bad" and only 22
percent said it was "good."
</P>
<P>
Radikal (Radical):
</P>
<P>
-- Necmettin Erbakan, former Turkish prime minister, said
Sunday in Bonn, Germany, that the court decision outlawing his
former Welfare Party (RP) was against democracy.
</P>
<P>
The pro-Islamic RP was closed in January by Turkey's
Constitutional Court under the pressure of the powerful secularist
military.
</P>
<P>
Milliyet (National):
</P>
<P>
-- Russian officials have reiterated that Russia will deliver
the S-300 missiles to Cyprus on schedule despite strong
opposition from Turkey, the staunch supporter of Turkish Cypriots
living in the northern part of the divided island.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has warned that it will take all necessary measures to
prevent the missiles' deployment in Cyprus, saying they pose
threat to the security of Turkish Cypriots and Turkey. 
