<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southwestern China Balancing Power Supply and Demand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Two generators with a total
capacity of 1.1 million kw at the Ertan Hydro-electric Power
Station in China's Sichuan Province are expected to go into
operation this year.
</P>
<P>
This will bring the province's total generating capacity to
12.1 million kw and help the province effectively reach a balance
between its power supply and demand.
</P>
<P>
Local spending on construction in the power industry this year
has been increased to 14 billion yuan, from 11 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Work on new power projects in the province will be scheduled
for completion after 2003 and will give priority to large
hydro-electric and some thermal power units.
</P>
<P>
A number of power stations like the 3.3-million-kw Ertan
station, the 700,000-kw Baozhusi station, and the 600,000-kw
Guang'an station are expected to go into operation before the year
2000, adding five million kw to the province's generating capacity.
</P>
<P>
It will develop a group of power stations that will further
improve local electric power grids. 
</P>
</TEXT>
