<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Slick Feared as Ship Sinks in Kenya's Port </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Oil slick fear is spreading as a
cargo ship with fuel and chemical load went under inside Kenya's
Mombasa port, a leading Indian Ocean port in the whole east
African region.
</P>
<P>
The mv Mirage, a 300-ton vessel bound for Mogadishu, took in
water and sank with goods worth millions of Shillings, resulting
in an immediate environmental disaster alert, the Daily Nation
newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The 12-man crew of the sunk vessel have scrambled to safety,
said the report.
</P>
<P>
A Kenya Ports Authority anti-pollution vessel, mv Fagio,
rushed to the scene to try and arrest a possible oil slick. Port
police and maritime experts had a hectic time keeping away
looters and cordoning off the area.
</P>
<P>
As chemicals in the cargo met with the water, foul-smelling
and possibly toxic fumes engulfed the area and choked many people
on the berth.
</P>
<P>
The ship, which started going down at about 7:00 p.m.
Saturday, was wholly submerged by Sunday morning. Only
its top mast could be seen above the quay waters amidst the swirl
of broken cartons and an oilly surface.
</P>
<P>
Captain Harun Mohammed said the ship sank due to instability
caused by irregular loading which left it heavier on one side.
</P>
<P>
He said the vessel started listing on one side and took in
water. Efforts to pump out the water were fruitless.
</P>
<P>
He ruled out over-loading as it had not taken its full
capacity of 300 tons.
</P>
<P>
Among the cargo were tins of chlorine, medicine, tea leaves,
cigarettes, iron sheets, vehicle parts and clothing material.
</P>
<P>
The mv Mirage, formerly known as the Bonsella, sank in similar
circumstances inside the port of Tanga, Tanzania, two years ago
as it loaded goods for Mombasa. It was salvaged in an expensive
exercise which rendered it dormant until recently. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
