<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Wants to Build New Relationship With China: Clinton (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. President Bill
Clinton said here today that the U.S. wants to build a new
relationship with the rapidly developing China for a more peaceful
and prosperous world in the new era.
</P>
<P>
"Everything all of us know about the way the world is changing
and the challenges your generation will face tell us that our two
nations will be far better off working together than apart," said
Clinton in an address to the students and faculty members of
Beijing University, which he visited this morning.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. President said that both China and the U.S. should
work to see that the productive relationship the two countries now
enjoy blossoms into a fuller partnership in the new century.
</P>
<P>
"If that is to happen, it is very important that we understand
each other better, that we understand both our common interests and
our shared aspirations and our honest differences," said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the belief that an "open, direct exchange"
could both clarify and narrow the differences and give the people
a greater sense of confidence that a better future could be made.
</P>
<P>
Clinton stressed the necessity to talk about the "critical
importance" of "building a strong partnership between China and
the United States" to the Chinese students, whom he described as
"the next generation of China's leaders".
</P>
<P>
"Now your country has known more millennia than the United
States has known centuries," said the president. "This new century
can be the dawn of a new China, proud of your ancient greatness,
proud of what you are doing, prouder still of the tomorrows to
come."
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that the American people deeply admire China
for its major contributions to culture, religion, philosophy and
the arts of the world.
</P>
<P>
"Now we see China at a moment in history when your glorious
past is matched by your present sweeping transformation and the
even greater promise of your future," he added.
</P>
<P>
The president also spoke highly of the policy the Chinese
government has adopted during the recent Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
"China has steadfastly shouldered its responsibilities to the
region and the world in this latest financial crisis -- helping to
prevent another cycle of dangerous devaluations," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980629.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
