<DOCNO> XIE19980629.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Wants to Build New Relationship with China: Clinton (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Clinton said that in the upcoming 21st century featuring an
international financial system, the vibrant growth of China's
economy "is tied closely to the restoration of stability and
growth in the Asia Pacific region."
</P>
<P>
"We must continue to work together to counter this threat to
the global financial system and to the growth and prosperity
which should be embracing all of this region," he said.
</P>
<P>
In his address which lasted about half an hour, the U.S.
president also touched on the challenges which China and the
United States face, such as security in Asia, nuclear
proliferation, crimes, drugs, environment and financial security.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the two countries step up
cooperation in these fields.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also answered questions raised by some teachers and
students on Sino-U.S. relations, the Taiwan issue and U.S.
economy.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the Taiwan issue, Clinton reiterated that the
U.S. observes the one-China policy and abides by the principles
enshrined in the three Sino-U.S. joint communiques.
</P>
<P>
Prior to Clinton's speech, Beijing University President Chen
Jia'er made remarks welcoming the U.S. president and wife to visit
his university, adding that Chinese President Jiang Zemin
inspected the university two months ago.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that over the past century patriotism, progress,
democracy and science constitute fine traditions of the university
to march to the next century, adding that extensive international
exchange and cooperation are the motive force for the constant
progress Beijing University has made.
</P>
<P>
For a long time, Beijing University has kept good exchange and
cooperation with American universities, research institutes and
industrial and commercial circles, an epitome of booming
Sino-U.S. scientific, technological, cultural and educational
exchanges, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
"I believe the future of Sino-U.S. relations lies in the youth,
and the future of the youth in turn lies in education," Chen
Jia'er said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the sincere hope that young people of both
countries should have more understanding of each other, enhance
cooperation, create a better civilization for mankind and promote
the steady and healthy development of Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
More than 600 students and faculty members of the university
were present, which was followed by a ceremony at which the U.S.
president donated over 500 books in English to the university
library.  
</P>
</TEXT>
