<HEADLINE> Pak, U.S. to Begin Dialogue on New Chapter: U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Two visiting U.S. Senators told
the reporters Monday morning after their meeting with Foreign
Minister Gohar Ayub Khan that the U.S. and Pakistan will "begin a
dialogue on the new chapter."
</P>
<P>
Sam Brownback said that "we have had some very good initial
discussion" on the regional and bilateral matters.
</P>
<P>
"Our major objective here is to listen and begin a dialogue on
the new chapter between U.S. and Pakistan relationship," the U.S.
Senator said.
</P>
<P>
Brownback said that the U.S. and Pakistan have had a very long
relationship. However, "it's gotten frayed recently with the
things that have happened here. But We need to build further and
that is what the dialogue is about."
</P>
<P>
"So far we have had very good discussions on that," he added.
</P>
<P>
Another U.S. Senator Charles Robb said on the occasion that "we
had a very candid exchange of views this morning with the Foreign
Minister, which we appreciate."
</P>
<P>
The two U.S. Senators, who arrived here Sunday night, are the
first officials from the U.S. to visit Pakistan after its
detonation of nuclear devices at the end of May. They are expected
to meet with Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and Finance Minister
Sirtaj Aziz later in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Charles said that "our principle reason for coming to Pakistan
at this time is to listen and to begin the dialogue that will
help, hopefully, to re-establish the kind of relationship that
will benefit both countries and ultimately ease tensions in the
region which are understandably high at the moment."
</P>
<P>
While the two U.S. Senators are now in Pakistan, Pakistan's
Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmed is in the U.S. as the special
envoy of the Prime Minister to engage discussions with the U.S.
leadership.  
</P>
