<HEADLINE> US First Lady Visits Women's Law Center At Beijing University </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The first lady of the United
States Hillary Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright,
this morning visited a center associated with Beijing University
for the women's law studies and services, where they discussed
with its law experts, professors and lawyers.
</P>
<P>
Mrs. Clinton and Albright, who was present at a gathering at
the university earlier to attend President Clinton's address, are
accompanying US president William Clinton in his state visit to
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The center's director, Lawyer Guo Jianmei, first gave an
account of the work her center has done in protecting the women's
rights and interests, safeguarding legal justice and pressing
ahead the law system concerning women.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, two women benefited from this center told the guests
the problems they are facing and the efforts the center has made
and legal assistance it provided for them.
</P>
<P>
After hearing on the introduction on the center's work,
attorney-turned Hillary, extended her congratulations on the
efforts the center has made "in protecting the rights and
interests of women, and advancing their progressive cause.
</P>
<P>
She expressed her joy over the decision of the United States
and China to increase cooperation and exchanges between their
governments and non-government legal agencies.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, she expressed the hope that the center will do a
still better job in providing legal aid to the women in need,
studying cases concerning the infringement on the women's rights
and interests, as well as training young lawyers.
</P>
<P>
During the discussion, U.S Secretary of State Albright said
China has made major progress on turning commitment into reality
in the field of legal building, and she expressed the hope that
cooperation and exchanges will help exert a "positive impact"
over the country's legal reform.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the discussion that lasted nearly an hour,
Hillary received a stainless-steel memorial plate.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1995, the Beida Women's Law Research &AMP; Service
Center, a specialized, non-governmental organization, is devoted
to the study issues concerning the women's rights and interests.
