<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protecting Tibetan Culture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- China's central and local
governments have worked hard to protect the cultural heritages
of the Tibetans, according to local officials in the Tibet
Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The national Constitution and the Law on Regional Autonomy of
Ethnic Groups both clearly define respect, protection,
inheritance, and development of the cultural heritage of ethnic
groups.
</P>
<P>
China has over 50 institutions involved in Tibetology,
employing more than 2,000 people. Hundreds of books on Tibet have
been published and dozens of seminars on various aspects of
Tibetan culture have been held.
</P>
<P>
The Tibetan language is widely studied in local schools, and
Tibetan and Chinese are compulsory subjects in primary and middle
schools, and local government documents, newspapers, radio
stations and television stations must use the two languages.
</P>
<P>
Since 1994, an effort has been made to adapt Tibetan words to
computer use, and standards for the use of Tibetan have been
published.
</P>
<P>
Tibetan medicine and pharmacology have been developed over the
past several decades. Tibet now has 14 Tibetan hospitals, and many
counties have their own Tibetan medicine departments.
</P>
<P>
Since 1983, the regional government has discovered 1,721
historical sites and published a great deal about Tibetan cultural
relics.
</P>
<P>
The central government has financed a regional museum and a
regional library, each costing more than 90 million yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
