<HEADLINE> Chinese Economist Sees Good Economic Growth This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Liu Guoguang, a prominent
economist and former vice-president of the Chinese Academy of
Social Sciences, was quoted by today's Shanghai Securities News as
saying that China's economy will pick up again in the latter half
of this year or early next year as a result of expanded domestic
spending and a relaxed credit policy.
</P>
<P>
Liu attribute the recent slowdown in economic growth to
inflation controls, economic restructuring in recent years, the
Asian financial crisis and the failures to implement
counter-measures.
</P>
<P>
However, Liu still believes that this year's target of 8
percent economic growth will be realized, mainly because of the
generally favorable conditions China now finds itself in.
</P>
<P>
He said that China's conditions in transportation, energy, raw
materials, agriculture, foreign exchange reserves, and inflation
are good.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the government has shifted from cooling down to
accelerating economic growth, and many parts of China have set
their own economic growth target at above 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Even though he gives his support to economic growth, he still
emphasises the importance of improving the economic structure and
economic returns.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
