<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Domestic Spending Still on Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Government decision to
increase domestic spending made earlier this year to accelerate
national economic growth has begun to show some results, "People's
Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Fixed assets investment increased 12.7 percent in the first
five months of this year, and work has started on 72
newly-approved projects that will cost 124.5 billion yuan in all.
</P>
<P>
The State Council, China's top governing body, has decided to
increase bank loans this year by 100 billion yuan, 50 billion yuan
of which will go to infrastructure projects and another 20 billion
to residential housing, the paper says.
</P>
<P>
In the same period, 48.5 billion yuan was used for 118 key
state projects, accounting for 29.7 percent of China's annual
budget, or 3.2 percent more than for the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Investment in railways increased 50 percent, at 9.9 billion
yuan, and for highways, 47.9 percent, at 30.5 billion yuan. Real
estate rebounded from negative growth in 1997, with 15.2-percent
growth during that period.
</P>
<P>
Industrial growth began to pick up in May, with industrial
added-value output up by 8 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
