<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's GDP Grows at 7 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Zeng Peiyan, minister of China's
State Development Planning Commission, was quoted by today's
"People's Daily", the country's leading newspaper, as saying that
the GDP for the January-June period will be around 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Zeng said that greater effort should be made to increase
economic growth in the latter half to meet the goal of 8 percent
for the whole of 1998. China has increased investment in
infrastructure to spur consumer demand and economic growth.
</P>
<P>
In the first five months, investment in agriculture, forestry,
animal husbandry, fisheries, and water control was up 10.4 percent
from the 1997 figure, while investment in real estate rose 15.2
percent. Investment in railways for the same period rose 50
percent and for highways, 47.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Some 59 percent of the housing spending went for apartments for
individual use, a rise of 3.4 percent, and apartment sales were up
45.4 percent, with 63.7 percent of those going to individuals.
</P>
<P>
The increased spending in agriculture, forestry, water control,
railways, highways, telecommunications, environmental protection,
and municipal works will continue, Zeng said, pointing to the need
for finding ways to speed up construction and concentrate manpower
and investment for priority industries.
</P>
<P>
In the coming months, he said, there will be more spending on
state-owned grain depots, power grids in rural areas, more
economic and practical housing, and ecologically-sound
construction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
