<DOCNO> XIE19980629.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interest Levels Down on Kenya Central Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Treasury Bill (TB) yields
continued to drop last week with the Central Bank of Kenya
(CBK)'s 91-day TBs auction yielding an interest level of 25.11
percent, down from 25.42 percent the previous week.
</P>
<P>
The CBK only accepted TBs worth 1.2 billion Shillings (20
million U.S. Dollars) at the lower interest rate compared to the
3.2 billion Shillings (53.3 million Dollars) tendered, the East
African newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
A CBK official explained the trend as part of the government's
efforts to reduce the domestic debt from public borrowing.
</P>
<P>
The down in TB yields, combined with measures to reduce cash
ratio from 16 to 15 percent with effective from July 1, have also
led to a drop in the base lending rates of most commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
Lending rates have averaged 28 percent and have been cited as
too high and unattractive for most businesses.
</P>
<P>
"The cash ratio does not attract interest and banks have to
charge a high interest rate to recover this from borrowing
customers," said a CBK official.
</P>
<P>
The official said the drop in base lending rates was a
positive and direct result of the reduction in cash radio.
</P>
<P>
The daily cash ratio was also reduced from 12 to 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
Barclays Bank, Standard-Chartered, Kenya Commercial Bank and
other commercial banks announced last week a one percent drop in
their base lending rates, which now average 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
If the lending rates drop further, it may spark off investor
borrowing, the experts said.
</P>
<P>
On the domestic debt currently at 160 billion Shillings (2.7
billion Dollars) and being serviced at 43 million Shillings
(716,666 Dollars) monthly, they said externalizing the debt may
lead to inflation if all the government debtors are paid off.
</P>
<P>
In addition, external debts may have stringent time-specific
repayment periods which must be met, unlike the domestic debt
which the government can roll over with a new TB auction, they
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
