<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Resume Passenger Service on Lake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Kenya Railways Corporation
(KRC) will resume domestic passenger transport on Lake Victoria
in July after nearly one year's suspension of the services.
</P>
<P>
KRC has rehabilitated three vessels with modified locomotive
engines fitted to improve the services on the world's second
largest fresh water lake, the East African weekly newspaper
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Passenger services in Lake Victoria were suspended last year
after the water hyacinth covered a large area of water routes,
leading to high maintenance costs, said the report.
</P>
<P>
"We want to start with the Mbita, Mfangano, Takawiri, Uyoma
and Asembo bay routes, which i am sure are viable," said Gordon
Owino, KRC's Marine Superintendent.
</P>
<P>
The Homa Bay and Kendu Bay routes are left out because the
two areas are easily accessible by road and will necessitate a
change in time-table.
</P>
<P>
However, there are no plans to re-introduce international
passenger services linking Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania, according
to the report.
</P>
<P>
A Tanzanian vessel, mv Bukoba, which used to provide the
regional service, sank in 1995, killing some 800 passengers.
</P>
<P>
In another development, an overnight passenger train from
Nairobi arrived in the Lake Victoria port town of Kisumu on
Sunday -- the first since El Nino floods and landslides washed
away part of the line two months ago.  
</P>
</TEXT>
