<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Opens Court Trials to Public </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- At 8:30 a.m today, Wang Xiangqian,
a teacher from the Beijing Agriculture College, rushed to the
Beijing No.1 Intermediate People's Court to hear a court trial.
</P>
<P>
"The case to be tried today has nothing to do with me," said
Wang, "I came here just to see how a case is tried in court," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Beijing No.1 Intermediate People's Court issued a circular
recently stipulating that, effective June 10, Chinese citizens 18
and older are allowed to attend court hearings by presenting
appropriate identification, with journalists permitted to report
on any open trials.
</P>
<P>
This is the country's first intermediate court to enhance
external supervision by opening trials to the public. Open trials
are part of China's basic judicial system. According to related
Chinese laws, all cases -- excluding those involving state
secrets, privacy and those cases specially ruled by concerned laws
-- should be tried openly and allow non-clients to hear the trials
and allow reporters to cover the trials.
</P>
<P>
However, the open trials have not been implemented fully due to
the small number of courts, a large number of cases and the length
of time for court hearings.
</P>
<P>
Beijing No.1 Intermediate People's Court has invested more than
200,000 yuan (24,096 US dollars) to install electric screens and
safety examination facilities before allowing citizens to attend
court hearings by presenting identity cards.
</P>
<P>
The court also has worked out corresponding regulations and
work disciplines.
</P>
<P>
Wang Xiangqian, with a hearing certificate in hand, wrote down
the trial time and name of the case provided on an electric screen
at the west gate of the court.
</P>
<P>
At 8:50, Wang was allowed to take a visitors' seat in the court.
</P>
<P>
The case to be tried in the court involved compensation for
smuggled mobile phones.
</P>
<P>
Pan Gang, judge of the court, said that open hearings require
judicial staff members to work hard and improve their ability to
handle cases.
</P>
<P>
The new system has been warmly welcomed by local lawyers who
said that the system enhances supervision by the public on court
investigation and debate and also stimulates lawyers and court
workers to improve their personal quality and the capability to
use laws.
</P>
<P>
More than 80 Beijingers and journalists have attended court
hearings each week at the Beijing No.1 Intermediate People's Court
since the new system was adopted on June 10.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980629.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Residents Spend Less Time on Cooking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai residents have shortened
their cooking time by 50 percent compared to five years ago.
</P>
<P>
The difference has been attributed to a change in the living
pattern of local people and the rapid development of service
industry.
</P>
<P>
At present, the average daily cooking time for a three-member
family is 69 minutes, while that of five years ago was 125
minutes.
</P>
<P>
Increasing pressure from work and a strong desire for
entertainment have driven more Shanghai residents to eat prepared
foods and vegetables and go to restaurants.
</P>
<P>
Local chain stores and supermarkets can provide some 30 kinds
of semi-finished vegetables and food, and some provide dishes
according to customers' desires.
</P>
<P>
A survey has shown that most Shanghai residents want to shorten
their cooking time within 45 minutes daily to save time for study
and entertainment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
