<HEADLINE> South China Uses Decomposable Lunch Boxes on Trains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Liuzhou Railway Bureau
has begun to use paper lunch boxes to replace plastic foam ones on
34 trains under its administration.
</P>
<P>
The bureau in south China handles more than 23.8 million
passengers every year. The plastic-foam boxes which used to be
employed on its trains had caused serious white pollution along
the railway lines.
</P>
<P>
"The new boxes will decompose within a month, and will not
result in long-term pollution to the environment," said an
official with the bureau.
</P>
<P>
The bureau has also set up 14 garbage centers along the 2,000
kilometers of railway lines under its administration, and
tightened the management of garbage on trains.
</P>
<P>
"White pollution has been brought under control here," the
official said.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that all the fast-food sold on the trains soon
will be packaged in the new type of paper boxes.  
</P>
