<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Desert Reclamation Project To Benefit Yellow River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HUHHOT, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Reclaiming the Kubch Desert in the
Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region could improve the water quality
in the middle and lower reaches of the Yellow River, said a
Japanese desert reclamation expert and his Chinese partner.
</P>
<P>
Seiei Tohyama, 92, presides over the Kubch Desert reclamation
project. The elderly Japanese said he came to that conclusion on
the river after working in the desert for nearly 10 years with
Chinese partner Wang Haiming.
</P>
<P>
The Kubch Desert, one of China's eight major deserts, is
located on the south of China's Yellow River and is the source of
one-fourth of the sand in the river. In summer, heavy rains wash
more than 300 million tons of sand into the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
"To reclaim the desert with flood and to control flood with
sand" is the successful experience of the Chinese and Japanese
developers of Engbey, which lies in the recesses of the Kubch
Desert.
</P>
<P>
Planting trees and restoring vegetation is the main task of
reclaiming the desert in Engbey, said Tohyama, who added that
nearly 10,000 Japanese volunteers have come here to plant trees.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the flood season each summer, the Engbey developers
build a sand dam, which is several kilometers long, to block the
floodwaters.
</P>
<P>
When the water rushes into the enclosed sand dam, it flattens
dunes with the force of water and wind. The flood carries large
amounts of mud and humus from the Ordos Highland, and a fine
stretch of arable land forms as a result.
</P>
<P>
In this way, not only is the desert reclaimed, but the flooding
also is controlled.
</P>
<P>
At present, 2,000 hectares of arable land planted with 2
million trees has been developed in the 20,000-hectare in Engbey,
which used to be an isolated desert without residents 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Some 6,600 hectares of desert have also been reclaimed in
Engbey and the percentage of forest cover has climbed to 90
percent from the previous 5 percent, said Wang Haiming, director
of the desert development exemplary zone of Engbey.
</P>
<P>
Developers also built two reservoirs and a canal by enclosing
gullies that formed after the encroachment of floods. The
reservoirs and canal can store as much as 100 million cubic meters
of water.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980629.0210 </DOCNO>
