<HEADLINE> Incentive Projects for Investment Fall in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Board of Investment (BoI) in
Thailand approved promotional privileges for 328 projects worth
130 billion baht (3.17 billion U.S. dollars) during the first five
months of this year, far below the 414 projects a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Some 414 projects worth 196 billion baht (7.84 billion dollars)
were recorded during January to May in 1997, the Bangkok Post said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
By way of comparison, during the period, investors were
primarily interested in electronics, agro-industry and garments
and textiles.
</P>
<P>
The BoI approved 65 projects in the electronics sector which
represent 19.8 percent of total approvals against 13.5 percent in
1997.
</P>
<P>
The agro-industry and light industry also saw an increase over
the period.
</P>
<P>
The BoI said the approved projects could create 65,322 jobs for
the period.
</P>
<P>
Japan remained the biggest investor during the period, with 95
projects approved, though down from 126 projects over the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
Europe ranked second with 56 projects approved compared with 49
projects a year before. Investment projects from the United States
also went up to 41 from 27 of last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
