<HEADLINE> Finnish Media Follow Closely Clinton's China Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Major Finnish newspapers are
paying close attention to U.S. President Bill Clinton's China
visit, hailing that the historic event would enhance the
partnership between the two powers and exert great influence on
the world situation.
</P>
<P>
The national newspaper, Helsingin Sanomat, said in an editorial
on Saturday that Clinton's trip was one of the most significant
events in the world this year and that the economic reality played
an important role in his visit.
</P>
<P>
The editorial also noted China's economic reforms and growing
prosperity have created a market that attracts even the most
powerful country in the world.
</P>
<P>
China's unrelenting efforts not to devalue its currency RMB
have already won high praises from the world, it said.
</P>
<P>
An editorial in the leading Finnish newspaper, Aamulehti, said
Friday that China, with a 1.2 billion population, could not be
isolated. It would be impossible for the world to achieve economic
stability without China, said the editorial.
</P>
<P>
It said that China's efforts to ease the economic crisis,
including promising not to devalue its currency RMB, have earned
worldwide appreciation. The Asian giant was proceeding to a market
economy step by step with democracy and freedom following closely
behind, the editorial added.
</P>
<P>
Another Finnish newspaper, Etela-Suomen Sanomat, said in a
commentary Friday that the top priority of Clinton's China trip
was to develop friendship and trade relations between the U.S. and
China.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also have similar interests in the Asian
financial crisis, tension and concerns over nuclear proliferation
provoked by India's and Pakistan's nuclear tests, the commentary
said. 
