<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Credit Set to Boost Thai Imports From Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 29 (Xinhua) -- An export credit worth more than
100 million U.S. dollars from an Italian financial institution is
ready to be granted to Thai industrial manufacturers importing
Italian capital goods, the newspaper The Nation reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Franco Passaro, trade commissioner of the Italian Trade
Commission, said the 100 million dollar credit, supported by
Mediobanca, an Italian private financial institution, was geared
to help the Thai industrial sector through the Industrial Finance
Corporation of Thailand (IFCT).
</P>
<P>
The minimum contract value to be granted through the loan is
750,000 dollars per project. Mediobanca will offer financing for
85 percent of the total contract value, with the remainder being
paid in cash by Thai importers.
</P>
<P>
The life span of the loan is around five to eight years with an
interest rate close to the London Interbank Borrowing Rate
(Libor), the newspaper quoted Passaro as saying.
</P>
<P>
The funds will be extended to match rising credit demand.
Passaro said this credit would assist the industrial sector to
make productivity and efficiency more competitive in the world
market.
</P>
<P>
To survive in tough competition, technology and product quality
need to be upgraded, he said.
</P>
<P>
The current economic crisis has led to shrinking Italian
machinery imports, which was worth 5.2 million dollars last year
compared with 19.64 million dollars in 1996 and 21.37 million
dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
According to Passaro, several Italian investors are eyeing
Thailand for investment, particularly in the sectors of frozen
food processing, textiles, plastic machinery and property.
</P>
</TEXT>
