<HEADLINE> President Clinton on Improving Mutual Understanding Between China, U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton today
expressed the hope that his state visit to China would help
improve mutual understanding and respect between the people of
China and the United States.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that my trip would help to show a full and balanced
picture of modern China to the U.S., and that my coming here would
encourage others to come here, and others to participate in the
life of China," the President told students and faculty of Beijing
University, which he visited this morning.
</P>
<P>
At a gathering of nearly 1,000 people, a student of the
university pointed out that the Americans don't know as much about
the Chinese as the Chinese do about them, and asked President
Clinton what he planned to do to change this situation.
</P>
<P>
Calling the question "a very good point," Clinton said that one
of the reasons for his visit to China is to improve the mutual
understanding and respect between the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
He said he hopes many more Americans would come here to study,
to tour and to do business.
</P>
<P>
However, he conceded that "there is no easy answer" to the
student's question, and that "it's something we have to work at."
</P>
