<DOCNO> XIE19980629.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Sri Lanka Affected by East Asian Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka, which was initially not
affected by the East Asian currency crisis, is now feeling the
impact.
</P>
<P>
Within the last week the Colombo Stock Exchange recorded a drop
of 5.22 percent, the second biggest after a 6.07-percent decline
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The all share price index closed at 606.4 points, down from
639.8, and the sensitive index closed at 926.6, down from 977.1.
Turnover also dropped drastically to 1.27 million U.S. dollars at
the weekend from 4.23 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Countries in the Asian region have since July last year had a
rough time in terms of investment. The Colombo Stock Market too
has witnessed a net outflow of foreign funds amounting to 24.1
million dollars with a net outflow of 6.65 million dollars in May
this year alone.
</P>
<P>
The rivalry between India and Pakistan for nuclear supremacy in
the South Asian region has only made the crisis worse for Sri
Lanka. The total share capital fund base of the stock exchange now
stands at 1.8 billion dollars of which only 25 percent is foreign
share capital.
</P>
<P>
At the moment the quantum of foreign investment coming in is
negligible. Foreign purchases in May 1998 was 8.95 million dollars
while the sale of shares held by foreigners was nearly double that
figure at 15.61 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Businessmen here bemoaned that the stock market is "reeling"
but they are hopeful that foreign fund managers will return once
the regional crisis settles. When that will be nobody could
confirm, however.
</P>
<P>
Economic analysts here said Sri Lanka's local economy is sound,
with local companies having recorded good profits. Especially the
plantation sector has performed extremely well.
</P>
<P>
Despite favorable conditions, there is no overall upward
movement  in the market as Sri Lanka leans heavily on foreign
funds. Hence it has been impossible to avoid the impact of the
regional crisis.
</P>
<P>
With currencies in Malaysia, Singapore, Japan and India being
devalued, Sri Lanka will find it difficult to compete
internationally if it does not devalue its currency.
</P>
<P>
However, the central bank believes that there is no need for
any sudden devaluation. The Sri Lankan currency is allowed to
adjust on its own and on this basis, it has already depreciated by
6 to 8 percent so far this year.
</P>
<P>
Authoritative financial sources here recently have warned that
foreign funds operating in the region might dry up totally and
they are likely to flee South Asia altogether to avoid the impact
of sanctions against India and Pakistan imposed for their nuclear
tests in May.
</P>
<P>
Local investors have been cautioned that it is not prudent to
buy shares held by foreign investors which are on offer these days
as such shares are said to bear a very high price in value and
they would provide liquidity for the foreign companies moving out.
</P>
<P>
Projects undertaken by foreign investors particularly from
Asian countries have virtually come to a standstill in Sri Lanka.
The investors are short of funds due to the currency crisis and
some of them are even putting their investments up for sale.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Finance Minister G. L. Peiris is however optimistic and
said that it is only temporary that the investors are moving out
and that the Sri Lankan government is finding alternative means to
attract other investors.
</P>
<P>
He sees no need to devalue the Sri Lankan rupee as it is not
artificially propped up. He even deems the sanctions imposed on
India and Pakistan as an opportunity for Sri Lanka to attract
investment.
</P>
<P>
To prevent cheap goods flowing into Sri Lanka because of the
currency devaluation in neighboring countries, Peiris said Sri
Lanka will introduce anti-dumping legislation.
</P>
<P>
Peiris claimed that Sri Lanka has not suffered as much from the
currency crisis as some other countries in Asia because Sri
Lanka's macroeconomic fundamentals are sound.
</P>
<P>
Former Finance Minister Ronnie De Mel rules out the chances of
the East Asian crisis frizzling out soon. He believes that the
effect of the large-scale devaluation of currencies in countries
in the region will have a serious impact on Sri Lanka's economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980629.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. President on Reunification of China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton today
reiterated that the United States will stick to its one-China
policy, arguing that the U.S. sales of weapons to Taiwan is not an
obstacle to the peaceful reunification of China's mainland and
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Clinton made the remark in response to a question posed by a
Beijing University student on whether U.S. arms sales to the
Taiwan and the renewed U.S.-Japan security treaty, reportedly
covering Taiwan, run against the U.S. government's one-China
policy.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he reaffirmed the U.S. policy that recognizes only
one China in the meeting with Chinese President Jiang Zemin
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the U.S. encourages the cross-Taiwan Straits
dialogue to achieve a peaceful reunification.
</P>
<P>
"Our policy is that any weapons sales therefore to Taiwan must
be for defense purposes only," Clinton asserted, " and China must
not believe we are in anyway trying to undermine our own one-China
policy."
</P>
<P>
On the renewed U.S.-Japan Security Treaty, he claimed that the
U.S.-Japan security agreement is not directed against any country.
</P>
</TEXT>
