<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. President Clinton Visits Beijing University </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton who is
on China visit today visited the prestigious Beijing University,
also known as Beida, and make a speech to its faculty and
students.
</P>
<P>
Arriving at the campus around 10:00 local time a.m. (02:00 GMT),
President Clinton is scheduled to make his speech soon.
</P>
<P>
According to a advance copy of his speech, Clinton says, "As
you build a new China, America wants to build a new relationship
with you for a new century. We want China to be successful, secure
and open...working with us for a more peaceful and prosperous
future."
</P>
<P>
"...I would like the productive relationship we now enjoy to
blossom into a fuller partnership for the new century," Clinton
says.
</P>
<P>
Beida President Chen Jia'er made welcoming remarks before
Clinton's speech.
</P>
<P>
"We are happy to see that President Clinton is on a successful
return visit to China following Chinese President Jiang Zemin's
successful visit to the U.S. last fall," he said.
</P>
<P>
The entire university sincerely hopes that China and the U.S.
will continue with their efforts to make still greater
contribution to world peace, stability and prosperity in the 21st
century, he added.
</P>
<P>
After addressing students and faculty, Clinton will stroll on
the campus to Beida's new library, the largest of its kind in
Asia, where he will donate 555 new books weighing about one metric
ton.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. president is scheduled to leave for Shanghai later
today.
</P>
<P>
China and the United States are expected to sign seven economic
and trade contracts and agreements involving a total of 2.1
billion U.S. dollars this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The gathering is being televised live. 
</P>
