<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar's Communications Up in 1997-98 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar stepped up installation of
modern communications facilities in the 1997-98 fiscal year,
bringing about a 16.3-percent growth in the sector's services
value over the previous year, said a latest official economic
report.
</P>
<P>
To expedite its posts and telecommunications services, Myanmar
extended its mail services including express money order services
in the fiscal year ending March, a current report of the country's
financial, economic and social conditions said.
</P>
<P>
Especially since the beginning of the fiscal year, the Myanmar
communications authorities have been carrying out the foremost
express postal services in collaboration with the Netherlands' DHL
Worldwide Express Ltd. on a joint-venture basis, linking 227
countries, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar also expanded the installation of facsimiles, sending
telegraphs by computers for rapid communications services.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Myanmar extended construction of long-distance lines,
installation of new microwave links and auto-telephone exchange
lines in rural and border areas.
</P>
<P>
Since the establishment of microwave links in 1995, the capital
of Yangon had been able to connect with nine other cities through
the system at the end of the fiscal year, it said.
</P>
<P>
The number of telephones in Myanmar also increased by 33,000 in
1997-98 to exceed 232,000. Of the telephones, cellular phones rose
by 1,700 in number, adding up to 8,947.
</P>
<P>
The number of international direct dialing (IDD) telephones
went up to 2,907 from 1,914 and that of facsimiles to 1,945 from
1,695.
</P>
<P>
A total of 62 towns and cities had already had auto-telephones
at the end of the fiscal year, it stated.
</P>
<P>
In 1997-98, Myanmar began introducing a CDMA radio-telephone
system in the capital with an initial 3,000 lines in operation.
</P>
<P>
For overseas services, the country added more than 800
telephone channels in the year to directly link 16 countries.
</P>
<P>
Under an Asia-Europe marine communications project, Myanmar
participated in building terminal stations in the year,
anticipating further improvement in international telephone
communication services.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's posts and telecommunications sector contributed 1.6
percent to the gross domestic product in the 1997-98 fiscal year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
