<HEADLINE> Philippines' Budget Deficit Seen to Surge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government's budget
deficit is expected to rise to as high as 21 billion pesos (525
million U.S. dollars) in the first half of the year, a newspaper
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We are already off track vis-a-vis the country's fiscal
program this year... Estimates for the first semester deficit run
to as high as 21 billion pesos," incoming Finance Secretary
Edgardo Espiritu was quoted as saying by Manila Bulletin.
</P>
<P>
The budget deficit was already 15.4 billion pesos (385 million
dollars) at the end of May following a revenue collection
shortfall brought about by a slowing economy.
</P>
<P>
The government has committed under an International Monetary
Fund program to post a 5-billion-peso (125 million dollars)
surplus by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
According to Espiritu, however, the year-end budget position
would reach a deficit of about 40 billion pesos (1 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The rising budget deficit is seen to keep banks' interest rates
high and force the government to reduce allocation for
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu and other members of the new cabinet will assume
office Tuesday afternoon after President-Elect Joseph Estrada
takes his oath of office at noon Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
