<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar's Private Economy Develops in 1997-98 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar's private economy achieved
sustainable development in the 1997-98 fiscal year ending March,
contributing 75.4 percent to the country's gross domestic product
(GDP), according to the latest official statistics.
</P>
<P>
In the three main goods sectors which contributed the most to
the GDP in the year, the private enterprises shared 97.6 percent
in its output value in agriculture, 98.2 percent in meat and fish
and 72.2 percent in manufacturing, said a current report on the
country's financial, economic and social conditions.
</P>
<P>
Of the services sector, private firms took up 90.7 percent in
services value in rental and others and 65.5 percent in transport.
</P>
<P>
Of the trade sector, private businesses made up 76 percent of
the trade volume, sharing 67.8 percent of the export value of 1
billion U.S. dollars, the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to another report of the official Trade News, the
number of private businesses operating in Myanmar increased by
4,072 in 1997, reaching 23,464 at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The number of exporters and importers jumped by 1,632, that of
local companies by 2,102 and foreign firms or branches by 235.
</P>
<P>
There were also 2,075 business representatives, 1,201
partnership firms, 122 joint ventures and 35 chambers of commerce
in the country at the end of the year, the report added.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's GDP registered a 4.6-percent growth in 1997-98, in
which the goods sector rose by 4.3 percent, the services sector by
7.4 percent and the trade sector by 3.2 percent as compared with
the previous year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
