<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Companies In East China Province Tapping Global Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Qiu Jibao, a farmer from Taizhou
County in east China's Zhejiang Province, set up a small sewing
machine factory with his hard-earned savings 12 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Since then, he has seized every opportunity to expand his
business abroad. He first cracked the Peruvian market and now his
products sell well in South America, the United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
His company manufactures 600,000 sewing machines a year to
become one of the largest in China.
</P>
<P>
Eighty percent of Qiu's products are exported to 73 countries
and regions, which ranks his enterprise first among its Chinese
counterparts in earning foreign exchange for five consecutive
years.
</P>
<P>
Qiu's success story is not surprising in Zhejiang. Many local
companies have established branches or offices abroad to
streamline the export of local products and small commodities.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than 3,200 local private enterprises have been
engaged in exporting, with annual earnings of 6 billion yuan (722
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The success of private enterprises has also aroused the
attention of the provincial government, which has vowed to give
more preferential treatment to private enterprises.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
