<DOCNO> XIE19980629.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over-Pessimism Will Cause Recession: Singapore Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, JUNE 29 (XINHUA) -- Singapore Senior Minister Lee
Kuan Yew said here Sunday night that over-pessimism will cause
recession in face of the present economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
Addressing at a fund-raising dinner held by the Tanjong Pagar
Community Development Council to mark its first founding
anniversary, Lee said Singaporeans must not become
over-pessimistic and drastically reduce spending because that will
cause the domestic economy to contract more.
</P>
<P>
He said Singapore's economy is in for a longer downturn than he
expected six months ago. But in all probability Singapore will
avoid negative growth this year unless further disastrous external
events intercede, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said Singapore had 5.8 percent growth in GDP in the first
quarter and preliminary figures show positive growth in the second
quarter. But the figures trend downward, he noted.
</P>
<P>
On ways to stimulate the economy, he said the best strategy is
to cut costs for employers to boost their competitiveness and
increase liquidity in the money market, and keep retrenchments to
a minimum.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore government is expected to announce in the
parliament later Monday the much-anticipated off-budget measures
to boost the economy.
</P>
<P>
The senior minister pointed out that the economic slowdown in
Singapore is not going to go away as easily as in 1985/1986
because then the cause of the recession was in Singapore and
problems could be corrected domestically.
</P>
<P>
He blamed the setbacks suffered by Singapore on external
factors including a deep regional downturn and a severe reduction
in external demand.
</P>
<P>
He said that this time the cause is not in Singapore, but in
the outside, in the region including Japan which has problems big
enough to affect the United States and the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Noting that recent economic and political troubles in Indonesia
and the economic recession in Japan have brought all economies in
East Asia to a lower level, he estimated that Singapore would take
 12 to 18 months to get out of the problems while its neighbors
might take two to three years.
</P>
<P>
"Singapore and the region will not fully recover until Japan
recovers and nobody at the present can say with confidence when
that will be," he stressed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
