<HEADLINE> Excerpts of Clinton's Remarks to Students, Faculty at Beida </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton will
deliver a speech to students and faculty of Beijing University
(Beida) this morning during his tour of the campus. The following
are excerpts of his speech:
</P>
<P>
"As you build a new China, America wants to build a new
relationship with you for a new century. We want China to be
successful, secure and open... working with us for a more
peaceful and prosperous future. There are those in my country who
question whether working with China is in our interests. There are
those in China who ask whether closer relations with the United
States make sense for China. But everything we know about the way
the world is changing and the challenges your generation will face
tell us that our two nations will be better off working together
than apart."
</P>
<P>
"... I would like the productive relationship we now enjoy to
blossom into a fuller partnership for the new century. If that is
to happen, it is important that we understand each other better --
Our common interests and aspirations and our differences. I
believe the kind of open, direct exchange President Jiang and I
had Saturday -- which I know many of you watched on television --
can both clarify and narrow our differences, and more important,
can change lives for the better." 
</P>
</TEXT>
