<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, June 29 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS -- Greece and Italy agreed Sunday that the United
Nations Security Council should tackle the Kosovo crisis so as to
avoid a possible war in the Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after their talks in the western Greek island of Corfu
before leaving together for Frankfurt to attend the official
installation of Wim Duisenberg as President of the European
Central Bank (ECB), Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis and his
Italian counterpart Romano Prodi warned that any armed conflict in
the Yugoslav province of Kosovo should be avoided as a war would
have wider repercussions on the countries in the Balkan region,
including Greece and Italy. (Greece-Italy-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair was "very
confident" about Northern Ireland's future and said on Sunday the
people had voted for a "new politics."
</P>
<P>
A spokesman said the prime minister told leaders of major
parties committed to the new assembly in Northern Ireland that
"there is every reason to be optimistic when 75 percent of the
voters backed parties in favor of the agreement." (UK-N. Ireland)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- French President Jacques Chirac said France
wants to cooperate with all African countries and would allow
Africans to solve their problems by themselves.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with South African national television, the
SABC, Chirac denied that France was trying to expand its "sphere
of influence" in Africa. (SAfrica-Chirac-French Policy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) Sunday urged
Iraq to take necessary steps to prove goodwill to its neighbors in
an effort to achieve peace and stability in the Gulf, Kuwait News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued after a one-day meeting in Saudi capital
Riyadh, the foreign ministers of GCC's six members reiterated the
demand that Iraq "admit the mistakes of invading Kuwait and its
violation of Arab and international laws and norms."
(Kuwait-GCC-Iraq)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ATHENS -- U.S. presidential envoy for Cyprus Richard Holbrooke
has warned the crisis in Serbia's southern province of Kosovo
could develop into war.
</P>
<P>
Describing the Kosovo situation as "explosive", Holbrook told
the Athens newspaper "To Vima" on Sunday that clashes between
Belgrade and the ethnic Albanians seeking independence from
Yugoslavia could "at any moment develop into war".
(US-Envoy-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- U.N. Special Envoy Alvaro de Soto said here Sunday
that Secretary General Kofi Annan was concerned over the rising
tension in South Asia after India and Pakistan conducted nuclear
tests in May.
</P>
<P>
"The secretary general is concerned about the turn of events
that occurred in the region and that is why he has taken unusual
steps by sending me here," Soto told reporters after meeting with
Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan. (Pakistan-UN Envoy)
</P>
