<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Military Atlas from World War II Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 29 (Xinhua) -- A Japanese military atlas of
China used in World War II has been found here, providing more
evidence of Japan's aggression of China during that period.
</P>
<P>
The "Pocket Atlas of China" was printed by a publishing house
in Tokyo on March 1, 1943, according to its back cover.
</P>
<P>
The atlas has a deep green cover and is the size of an adult's
hand. It includes 13 folded maps, each 35.5 centimeters (cm) long
and 17 cm wide when unfolded.
</P>
<P>
The content page of the atlas lists the names of the 13 maps
which include "Map of China," "Guangdong and Guangxi," "Xinjiang"
and "Tibet." Taiwan is not included on any of the maps.
</P>
<P>
On the "Map of China," the northeast three provinces of China
were marked outside China's border and were named "Manchuria,"
which completely exposed the aggressive ambitions and actions of
the Japanese militarists to invade and occupy northeast China's
Heilongjiang, Liaoning and Jilin provinces during World War II.
</P>
<P>
The atlas is in the possession of Xue Guangyao, who got it from
his father, Xue Ming.
</P>
<P>
"My father was the secretary of the Changzhi County Committee
of the Communist Party of China in north China's Shanxi Province
during the anti-Japanese War," Xue said. "He seized seven atlases
including the 'Pocket Atlas of China' from Wang Dehou, a puppet
army officer, at a battle."
</P>
<P>
"Wang confessed he got the atlas from a Japanese lieutenant who
used it for military purposes," Xue said.
</P>
<P>
The other six atlases were lost during the Cultural Revolution
(1966-1976), according to Xue.
</P>
<P>
"This is the only one that survived," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
