<DOCNO> XIE19980629.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece, Italy Urge U.N. Security Council to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Greece and Italy agreed Sunday that
the United Nations Security Council should Tackle the Kosovo
crisis so as to avoid a possible war in the Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after their talks in the western Greek island of Corfu
before leaving together for Frankfurt to attend the official
installation of Wim Duisenberg as President of the European
Central Bank (ECB), Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis and his
Italian counterpart Romano Prodi warned that any armed conflict in
the Yugoslav province of Kosovo should be avoided as a war would
have wider repercussions on the countries in the Balkan region,
including Greece and Italy.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that the U.N. Security Council should discuss and
deal with the Kosovo issue, Simitis said, while Prodi stressed
that any intervention should first be discussed by the U.N.
Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Simitis said that there would be a wave of refugees and a
general instability throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
As for relations between the two countries, Simitis said that
there must be cooperation between Greece and Italy on all matters
related to combating smuggling and crime.
</P>
<P>
Prodi said that the two countries should continue to
collaborate to make the Adriatic a crime-free sea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
