<HEADLINE> Blair: N.Ireland's Assembly will Succeed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 28 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
was "very confident" about Northern Ireland's future and said on
Sunday the people had voted for a "new politics."
</P>
<P>
A spokesman said the prime minister told leaders of major
parties committed to the new assembly in Northern Ireland that
"there is every reason to be optimistic when 75 per cent of the
voters backed parties in favor of the agreement."
</P>
<P>
In elections on Thursday, parties backing the Good Friday
accord, which set out a plan for the future of the British
province, won a large majority of the 108 seats in the assembly.
</P>
<P>
He said Blair and Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam had
earlier on Sunday spoken to the four main pro-accord party leaders
who between them control 76 seats, including Sinn Fein leader
Gerry Adams, and found them determined the new assembly would
work.
</P>
<P>
"The Prime Minister is very confident about the future. He
found among the party leaders he spoke to a very strong belief
that the assembly can work and an absolute determination that it
will," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Under the Northern Irish peace agreement, the assembly will be
run on a power-sharing basis, with Ulster Unionist Party leader
David Trimble likely to be first minister as his party won most
seats in the new assembly.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
